text: Peatland is a type of wetland ecosystem and is primarily composed of peat soil. It is defined as a wetland ecosystem which accumulates acidic peat, a deposit of dead plant material. Peatland is broadly synonymous with wetland and has related synonyms such as Peatland, bog, mire, morass, muskeg, and peat bog.

An estuary is a type of water body and is defined as a semi-enclosed coastal body of water with one or more rivers or streams flowing into it, and with a free connection to the open sea. It is also a type of entity that at least partially overlaps some coastal wetland ecosystems and has at least one stream mouth partially overlapping. Furthermore, "mouth" is considered a broad synonym for estuary, and "inlet" is a related synonym.

Hedge is a type of anthropogenic geographic feature, defined as a dense growth of shrubbery planted as a fence or boundary. It is exactly synonymous with HEDGE and hedgerow, and has a related synonym, shelter belt.

A navigation canal is a type of canal defined as an artificial watercourse with no flow or a controlled flow used for navigation. It is closely synonymous with "navigation canal" and is related to both "navigation channel" and "ship canal".

A geyser is a type of hot spring and is defined as a hot spring that erupts periodically, ejecting a column of hot water and steam into the air. It also has a broad synonym, which is "thermal feature."

A hot spring is a type of spring and also a type of entity that is at least adjacent to an entity which intersects with water and another entity that has an increased temperature quality. Hot springs can be categorized into three distinct types: alkaline hot springs, acidic hot springs, and neutral hot springs. The definition of a hot spring is a spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows. Moreover, "spring" is a broad synonym for hot spring, while "hotspring" and "thermal spring" are its exact synonyms.

A volcanic crater lake is defined as a lake contained within a volcanic crater, which is the same as the intersection of a crater lake and an entity that is at least located in some volcanic crater. Furthermore, a volcanic crater lake is categorized as a type of crater lake and also as a type of entity that is at least located in some volcanic crater.

A freshwater marsh is equivalent to an entity that intersects both a marsh and an entity that overlaps with a water body and is primarily composed of fresh water. It is classified as a type of marsh, overlaps with water bodies, and is primarily composed of fresh water. Moreover, a freshwater marsh is defined as a marsh where soils are saturated with water containing low concentrations of salts.

A saline marsh is defined as a marsh that intersects with water bodies that are primarily composed of saline water. It is a specific type of marsh that is also categorized as a type of water body that includes at least a part of a water body and is primarily composed of saline water. The definition of a saline marsh is a marsh whose water contains a considerable quantity of dissolved salts. In terms of terminology, saline marsh is broadly synonymous with "wetland" and has an exact synonym "salt marsh". Additionally, "salting" is considered a narrow synonym, while "salt marsh" and "tidal marsh" are related synonyms.

A saline evaporation pond is a type of pond that is characterized by at least having some part of saline water. It is defined as a shallow, man-made pond designed to produce salt from seawater through evaporation. This concept is broadly synonymous with a lake and has the exact synonym "salt evaporation pond." Additionally, it is relatedly referred to as a salt pond, salt ponds, or a saltern.
A fishpond is a type of lentic water body, defined as a pond or lake used for the artificial culture of fish.

A mangrove swamp is a type of coastal wetland ecosystem, which is a specific kind of ecological community primarily composed of whole plants. This ecosystem is characterized by having qualities that are either tropical or subtropical. It is defined as a swamp situated in tropical or subtropical environments, identified by communities of trees and shrubs thriving in saline coastal environments. The term "mangrove swamp" is broadly synonymous with woodland and is exactly synonymous with "mangal". Additionally, it is relatedly referred to as MangroveForest.

An underground lake is a type of lake and also a type of underground water body, defined as a lake that is formed under the Earth's surface. Such a lake may be associated with caves, aquifers, and springs.
An underground river, which is a type of river and also considered a type of underground stream, is defined as a river that is under the surface of the Earth.
An underground stream is both a type of stream and a type of underground water body, defined as a stream that is under the surface of the Earth.
An underground water body is a type of water body defined as a geographical feature associated with water that is under the surface of the earth.

A populated place is recognized as a type of environmental zone characterized by being at least the location of some building and also serving as a location for some homo sapiens. It is defined as a place or area that contains clustered or scattered buildings with a permanent human population. Furthermore, 'populated place' is broadly synonymous with 'place' and has exact synonyms including 'populated places' and 'settlement'. Additionally, it shares related synonyms such as 'inhabited region' and 'populated locality'.

A water body is a type of water mass and is also considered a type of entity that forms at least part of the hydrosphere and is primarily composed of water. It is defined as an accumulation of water of varying size and is broadly synonymous with the term hydrographic feature. Additionally, it has exact synonyms including aquatic feature, bodies of water, body of water, and waterbody.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

:road rdfs:subClassOf :constructed_pavement ;
    :has_definition "An open way for the passage of vehicles, persons, or animals on land."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_narrow_synonym "board walk"^^xsd:string,
        "caravan route"^^xsd:string,
        "causeway"^^xsd:string,
        "drive"^^xsd:string,
        "highway"^^xsd:string,
        "intersection"^^xsd:string,
        "parkway"^^xsd:string,
        "road bend"^^xsd:string,
        "road junction"^^xsd:string,
        "traffic circle"^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "accessway"^^xsd:string,
        "alley"^^xsd:string,
        "avenue"^^xsd:string,
        "boulevard"^^xsd:string,
        "cart track"^^xsd:string,
        "drove"^^xsd:string,
        "farm lane"^^xsd:string,
        "freeway"^^xsd:string,
        "lane"^^xsd:string,
        "roadway"^^xsd:string,
        "street"^^xsd:string,
        "thorofare"^^xsd:string,
        "thoroughfare"^^xsd:string,
        "thruway"^^xsd:string,
        "turnpike"^^xsd:string .
text: A road is a type of constructed pavement defined as an open way for the passage of vehicles, persons, or animals on land. It has several narrow synonyms that closely relate to its nature, including board walk, caravan route, causeway, drive, highway, intersection, parkway, road bend, road junction, and traffic circle. Additionally, road is associated with a broader range of related synonyms that encompass various forms of pathways and passages, such as accessway, alley, avenue, boulevard, cart track, drove, farm lane, freeway, lane, roadway, street, thorofare, thoroughfare, thruway, and turnpike.

Railway is a type of transport feature and has a definition as a permanent way having one or more rails which provides a track for cars. It also has a broad synonym, being referred to as a railroad feature. Moreover, railway has exact synonyms, including "RAILWAY" and "railroad."

A man-made tunnel is a type of tunnel, which is defined as a tunnel constructed by human means. It is broadly synonymous with both "tunnel" and "tunnels." Moreover, it has several narrow synonyms, including canal tunnel, railroad tunnel, road tunnel, and underpass.

A cave is a type of surface landform that is characterized by at least having parts such as some cave wall and some cave floor. Additionally, it is a type of entity that possesses the quality of having some incomplete closure. The definition of a cave is a naturally formed, subterranean open area or chamber. Furthermore, related synonyms for cave include cavern, grotto, and notch.
A tunnel is a type of channel and is defined as an underground or underwater passage. It has the exact synonym "TUNNEL" and is also related to synonyms such as "cave" and "natural tunnel".

A distributary is defined as a stream that branches off and flows away from a main stream channel, which is a common feature of river deltas. It is identified as a type of stream and also as a type that is at least a distributary of some hydrographic feature. Furthermore, a distributary is synonymous with a stream in both broad and narrow senses and is broadly synonymous with a watercourse. It is equivalent to an intersection of a stream and something that is at least a distributary of some hydrographic feature.

Human construction is the same as something that is the intersection of a material entity and at least the output of some human-directed construction process. It is a type of construction and also considered a part of the technosphere. Furthermore, human construction is recognized as an output of some human-directed construction process. It is defined as a construction that has been assembled by deliberate human effort and has the exact synonym "constructed feature."
A fault cave is a type of cave that is developed along a fault or fault zone. This development occurs either by movement of the fault or by preferential solution along it.

An aquaduct, which has the exact synonym aqueduct, is a type of canal. It is defined as a structure designed to transport water from a remote source, usually by gravity. Additionally, aquaduct has a related synonym, WATERCOURSE BRIDGE.
A building is a type of human construction and is characterized as something that at least has as part some building part. Additionally, it is defined as a permanent walled and roofed construction.

A dam is a type of constructed barrier with the definition of being a barrier constructed across a watercourse to control the flow or raise the level of water. Furthermore, dam has related synonyms such as barrage and dam site.

A bridge is a type of transport feature characterized as a built structure erected over a depression or obstacle to carry traffic or some facility such as a pipeline. It has several narrow synonyms including covered bridge, footbridge, and overpass.
A mine is a type of human construction and is also a type of entity that participates in mining activities. It is defined as an excavation in the Earth for the purpose of extracting earth materials.

An agricultural ecosystem is equivalent to the union of entities that are at the intersection of ecosystems and those that participate in or are formed as a result of agricultural processes. It is identified as a specific type of ecosystem. This ecosystem is closely associated with several terms that serve as its narrow synonyms, including barn, cattle dipping tank, corral, dairy, feedlot, grange, grazing allotment, irrigated field, nursery, pastoral site, sheepfold, and stockyard. Additionally, there are terms that are related synonyms to an agricultural ecosystem, such as AgriculturalLands, agricultural colony, agricultural facility, agricultural land, agricultural reserve, and agricultural site.

A farm is a type of agricultural ecosystem and also falls under the category of something that is at least partially constituted by the union of cropland and rangeland biomes. It is defined as an area of land used for the cultivation of crops or grazing of livestock, including any agricultural constructions therein. In terms of synonyms, "farm" has a broad synonym of "agricultural site" and an exact synonym of "FARM". Additionally, related synonyms include "farm", "farms", "farmstead", and "ranch".

Flume is a type of canal and has a definition as an open artificial water channel that leads water from a diversion dam or weir completely aside a natural flow, often an elevated box structure (typically wood) that follows the natural contours of the land. It has a broad synonym, watercourse, and an exact synonym, flume (manmade). Additionally, flume has a related synonym, canal.

A mountain range is a type of range of mounts that at least has part some mountain and is characterized by having at least 2 mountain components. It is defined as a range of mounts which is dominated by mountains. Furthermore, mountain range is related to several synonyms including cordillera, mountain chain, mountain group, and sierra.

A mountain is a type of mount and also a type of something that is at least formed as a result of a union of volcanic eruption and tectonic movement. It is defined as a landform that extends above the surrounding terrain in a limited area. Additionally, "Mountain" is an exact synonym for mountain, and it has a related synonym, "mountains."

A hill range is a type of range of mounts, and it is defined as a range of mounts which is dominated by hills. It is a type of entity that at least has some part that is a hill and has at least 2 hill components.

A hill is a type of mount and is defined as a rounded elevation of limited extent rising above the surrounding land with local relief of less than 300m. Additionally, hill has related synonyms including cerro, foothill, hill, hillock, hills, knoll, mount, and mountain.

A mountain pass is a type of surface landform, which is part of at least some mountain range and often has a U-shaped quality. It is defined as a lower point that allows easier access through a mountain range, generally taking the form of a saddle between two mountains. The exact synonym for a mountain pass is "pass," while related synonyms include "col," "defile," "gap," "notch," "saddle," "saddle (physiographic)," and "sill (physiographic)."
An alpine glacier is a type of glacier that is situated adjacent to at least some glacial valley. It is defined as a glacier contained in the site of a mountain valley.

A plain is a type of surface landform, which is characterized by at least having some flat quality. It is defined as a region of general uniform slope, comparatively level, and of considerable extent. Additionally, plain is related to synonyms such as interfluve, llanos, and outwash plain.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

:cliff rdfs:subClassOf :slope ;
    :has_definition "A slope which is part of a rocky elevation and which has a high degree of steepness."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "beach scarp"^^xsd:string,
        "bluff"^^xsd:string,
        "ceja"^^xsd:string,
        "ice cliff"^^xsd:string,
        "palisade"^^xsd:string,
        "precipice"^^xsd:string,
        "scar"^^xsd:string,
        "scarp"^^xsd:string,
        "scaw"^^xsd:string,
        "scraps"^^xsd:string .
text: Cliff is a type of slope with the definition of being a slope which is part of a rocky elevation and which has a high degree of steepness. It has related synonyms such as beach scarp, bluff, ceja, ice cliff, palisade, precipice, scar, scarp, scaw, and scraps.

A sea cliff is the same as something that is both a cliff and at least adjacent to some sea. It is a type of cliff that overlaps some sea coast and is adjacent to some sea. The definition of a sea cliff is a cliff that is a margin of a sea or ocean. Additionally, sea cliff has related synonyms such as coastal cliff and marine cliff.
An inland cliff is a type of cliff defined as one which is not adjacent to a major water body. Additionally, it has a related synonym, "crag."

A coastal plain is the same as an intersection of a plain and an entity that at least overlaps some sea coast. It is a type of plain and also a type of entity that at least overlaps some sea coast. Moreover, a coastal plain is defined as an area of flat, low-lying land adjacent to a coast and separated from the interior by other features.

A beach is described as a type of surface landform, which is part of a shore and primarily made up of sediment intersecting with materials like pebbles, cobbles, sand, gravel, and shells. It is defined as a landform consisting of loose rock particles such as sand, gravel, shingle, pebbles, cobble, or even shell fragments along the shoreline of a body of water. The term "Beach" is considered an exact synonym for beach, indicating they are precisely the same. Beaches have narrow synonyms including "beach berm" and "lagoon beach," suggesting these are specific types of beaches. Additionally, related synonyms to beach include "beach" itself, "beaches," "foreshore flats," "rivage," and "strand," implying these terms are closely associated with beaches but not exactly the same.

A sea beach is defined as a beach that is part of a sea shore, which intersects with something that is both a beach and at least part of some sea shore. It is a type of beach and also a type of entity that is at least part of some sea shore. Additionally, the term "sea beach" has an exact synonym, "strand."

A lacustrine beach is a type of beach that is defined as a beach which is part of a lake shore. It represents the intersection of being a beach and at least partly belonging to a lake shore. Essentially, a lacustrine beach is the same as something that is both a beach and at least partially part of some lake shore.

A volcanic feature is synonymous with a volcanic landform and is defined as a part of an astronomical body associated with a volcano - an opening, or rupture, in that body's surface or crust - which allows hot, molten rock, ash, and gases to escape from deep below the surface. It is identified as a type of surface landform and also as a type that has formed as a result of a volcanic eruption. Moreover, a volcanic feature is the same as something that represents the intersection of a surface landform and something that has at least formed as a result of a volcanic eruption.

A caldera is a type of crater and also a type of geological formation that is at least formed as a result of some volcanic eruption. It is disjoint with, meaning distinct from, a volcanic crater. Additionally, a caldera is defined as a feature formed by the collapse of land following a volcanic eruption and has a related synonym, which is "crater."

A desert area intersects with something that is both an area of barren land and something that at least has some quality of being arid. Moreover, a desert area is defined as a type of area of barren land, and it is also a type of something that at least has some quality of being arid. Additionally, a desert area is defined as a region rendered barren or partially barren by environmental extremes, especially by low rainfall. Furthermore, the desert area has a related synonym, which is an arid region.

An island is a type of planetary landmass and also a type of entity that is at least surrounded by a union of a wetland area and a water body. It is defined as an area of dry or relatively dry land surrounded by water or low wetland. Moreover, island has related synonyms including eyot, holm, hummock, isle, and islet.
An artificial island is a type of island that is constructed by human effort. Additionally, it is synonymously related to an offshore platform.

fragment:
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

:valley rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :formed_as_result_of ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :planetary_erosion ],
        [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_quality ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :elongated ],
        :geographic_basin ;
    :has_definition "A depression which has been formed as a result of erosion by water or ice and which is low-lying, bordered by higher ground, and especially elongate."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_narrow_synonym "chasm"^^xsd:string,
        "coulee"^^xsd:string,
        "dale"^^xsd:string,
        "glacial gorge"^^xsd:string,
        "glacial trough"^^xsd:string,
        "gulch"^^xsd:string,
        "gully"^^xsd:string,
        "median valley"^^xsd:string,
        "shelf valley"^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "glen"^^xsd:string,
        "goe"^^xsd:string,
        "gorge"^^xsd:string,
        "graben"^^xsd:string,
        "hollow"^^xsd:string,
        "lavaka"^^xsd:string,
        "moat"^^xsd:string,
        "ravine"^^xsd:string,
        "re-entrant"^^xsd:string,
        "seachannel"^^xsd:string,
        "strath"^^xsd:string,
        "trench"^^xsd:string,
        "vale"^^xsd:string,
        "water gap"^^xsd:string .
text: A valley is a type of geographic basin which also falls under the category of entities that are at least somewhat elongated and have formed as a result of some form of planetary erosion. Specifically, a valley is defined as a depression that has been shaped by the erosive action of water or ice, characterized by being low-lying, bordered by higher ground, and notably elongated. In terms of terminology, "valley" has narrow synonyms including chasm, coulee, dale, glacial gorge, glacial trough, gulch, gully, median valley, shelf valley, and related synonyms such as glen, goe, gorge, graben, hollow, lavaka, moat, ravine, re-entrant, seachannel, strath, trench, vale, and water gap.

Delta is a type of river mouth with a definition as a tract of alluvium formed at the mouth of a river where the deposition of some of its load exceeds its rate of removal, crossed by the divergent channels (distributaries) of the river. It has related synonyms including alluvial fan, bay delta, canyon delta, fan, fan delta, outwash, outwash plain, and pass (delta).
A cave entrance is a type of site and is also considered a type of entity that is at least part of some cave. Additionally, "Cueva de Altamira" is an exact synonym for a cave entrance.

A mangrove island is a type of island that is also characterized as being a type of entity that includes, at least in part, some mangrove swamp. It is defined as an island formed of trees and shrubs that grow in saline coastal habitats in the tropics and subtropics.

        "terrace"^^xsd:string,
        "tongue (seafloor)"^^xsd:string,
        "underwater feature"^^xsd:string,
        "valley"^^xsd:string,

text: An undersea feature is a type of hydrographic feature defined as a hydrographic feature located below the surface of a marine water body. This encompasses a variety of specific formations, including basins, escarpments, fans, flats, forks, furrows, gaps, gullies, holes, holes (seafloor), ledges, levees, median valleys, moats (seafloor), pinnacles, plains, plateaus, platforms, provinces, ramps, ramps (seafloor), ravines, ridges, rises, rises (seafloor), saddles, shelf edges, undersea banks, undersea basins, undersea benches, undersea cliffs, undersea fans, undersea forks, undersea fracture zones, undersea furrows, undersea gaps, undersea holes, undersea ledges, undersea levees, undersea median valleys, undersea moats, undersea peaks, undersea pinnacles, undersea plains, undersea platforms, undersea ramps, undersea rises, undersea saddles, undersea shelves, undersea shelf edges, undersea shelf valleys, undersea sills, undersea slopes, undersea spurs, undersea terraces, undersea tongues, undersea valleys, all of which are considered narrow synonyms of an undersea feature. Additionally, it has related synonyms that encompass broader terms associated with the oceanic and subsea environment, such as ocean floor features, seafloor features, sills, spurs, subsea features, terraces, tongues (seafloor), underwater features, valleys, and valleys, further emphasizing the diverse nature of hydrographic features found beneath the surface of marine water bodies.

The lake surface is a type of liquid air-water interface layer and also a type of surface of an astronomical body. Furthermore, it is a type of something that is at least part of some lake and is at least partially surrounded by some air.

Grassland area is a type of vegetated area and is also a type of something that at least overlaps some grassland ecosystem. It is defined as an area in which grasses (Graminae) are a significant component of the vegetation. Furthermore, grassland area is related to and synonymously referred to as grazing area and herbaceous area.
Heath is a type of vegetated area, defined as an upland moor or sandy area dominated by low shrubby vegetation including heather. Additionally, heath has a related synonym: wetland.

The meadow ecosystem, which is a type of grassland ecosystem, is defined as a grassland ecosystem that contains a variety of annual, biennial, and perennial plants growing on rolling or flat terrain. It is exactly synonymous with "meadow" and has a related synonym, "hay meadow."

:woodland_area rdfs:subClassOf :vegetated_area ;
    :has_definition "Land having a cover of trees, shrubs, or both."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_narrow_synonym "brigalow"^^xsd:string,
        "pine grove"^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "caatinga"^^xsd:string,
        "chanaral"^^xsd:string,
        "coniferous forest"^^xsd:string,
        "copse"^^xsd:string,
        "deciduous forest"^^xsd:string,
        "equatorial forest"^^xsd:string,
        "equatorial rain forest"^^xsd:string,
        "garique"^^xsd:string,
        "grove"^^xsd:string,
        "jungle"^^xsd:string,
        "mallee scrub"^^xsd:string,
        "monsoon forest"^^xsd:string,
        "moor"^^xsd:string,
        "mott"^^xsd:string,
        "motte"^^xsd:string,
        "mulga"^^xsd:string,
        "mulga scrub"^^xsd:string,
        "rain forest"^^xsd:string,
        "reforested area"^^xsd:string,
        "sagebrush"^^xsd:string,
        "scrub"^^xsd:string,
        "shrub"^^xsd:string,
        "silva"^^xsd:string,
        "stand"^^xsd:string,
        "taiga"^^xsd:string,
        "thicket"^^xsd:string,
        "thorn forest"^^xsd:string,
        "tropical rain forest"^^xsd:string,
        "wood"^^xsd:string,
        "wooded area"^^xsd:string .
text: A woodland area is a type of vegetated area defined as land having a cover of trees, shrubs, or both. It has narrow synonyms such as brigalow and pine grove. In addition, woodland area is related to a variety of other vegetated areas through synonyms including caatinga, chanaral, coniferous forest, copse, deciduous forest, equatorial forest, equatorial rain forest, garique, grove, jungle, mallee scrub, monsoon forest, moor, mott, motte, mulga, mulga scrub, rain forest, reforested area, sagebrush, scrub, shrub, silva, stand, taiga, thicket, thorn forest, tropical rain forest, wood, and wooded area.

A lava tunnel, which is also exactly known as a lava tube, is a type of volcanic cave and is characterized by being a type of structure that possesses some tubular quality. It is defined as a tunnel formed by the flow of molten lava, which has subsequently drained out.

A forested area is defined as an area with a high density of trees, where a small forest may also be referred to as a wood. It is the same as something that intersects with both woodland areas and areas that at least overlap some forest ecosystem. Furthermore, a forested area is categorized as a type of woodland area and also as a type of area that at least overlaps some forest ecosystem. Additionally, forested area is related to the synonyms "forest" and "wood."

The area of tundra is defined as a vegetated area which is part of a tundra ecosystem, and it is characterized by several key aspects. Firstly, it is a type of vegetated area that constitutes at least a part of the tundra biome and ecosystem. Additionally, it possesses qualities of tundra climatic conditions and partially overlaps with the tree line ecotone. Furthermore, the area of tundra is synonymous with terms like Arctic land and TundraEcosystem, indicating its significant relation to the Arctic regions and its ecosystemic importance.

An agricultural field is a type of field defined as a field located on land and used for agricultural purposes, such as the grazing of livestock or the cultivation of crops. It is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site and is relatedly synonymous with cropland and grassland.

An orchard is a type of plantation and is defined as an intentional planting of trees or shrubs maintained for food, typically fruit, production. Furthermore, orchard has broad synonyms including agricultural site and cropland.

A vineyard is a type of plantation defined as a place where grapes are grown for making wine, raisins, or table grapes. It is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site and cropland, and it also has an exact synonym: vineyards.

A plantation is a type of farm and also falls under a category that constitutes at least part of the cropland biome. It is defined as an intentional planting of a crop, on a large scale, usually for uses other than cereal production or pasture. The term is predominantly applied to tree and shrub plantings and is often associated with plantings maintained for economic reasons beyond subsistence farming. Furthermore, plantation is synonymously related to terms such as agricultural site, cropland, and plantation field.
A coconut plantation, which is a type of plantation, is also known as a coconut grove or wood.
A planted forest is a type of forest ecosystem that is defined as a forest intentionally established by human intervention.
An oil palm plantation is a type of plantation that is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site and is also related to a palm grove.

An artificial channel is a type of human construction and a type of channel of a watercourse. It is defined as a channel of a watercourse that has been constructed by humans or their technologies. Furthermore, related synonyms for an artificial channel include "flume" and "improved channel."
A track is a type of road that is generally a small road and typically not paved. It is also related to and synonymous with footpath, path, and trail.

A political entity is a type of administrative region defined as a geographical region whose affairs and population are administered by an authority. Additionally, "political entity" is also related to the synonym "political entity."

A supranational geopolitical entity is a type of political entity with the definition of being a political entity established by more than one state and possessing at least some influence over the affairs of its member states.

A mineral spring is a type of spring defined as a spring whose water contains a significant amount of dissolved minerals, derived from the rocks through which the water flows. It is broadly synonymous with the term "spring" and the hydrographic term "spring (hydrographic)."

A sulfur spring is a type of mineral spring, defined as a spring through which water with elevated levels of dissolved derivatives of sulfur flows. It is broadly synonymous with the term spring (hydrographic) and has an exact synonym, sulphur spring.

Badland is a type of surface landform and a type of entity that has at least some arid quality. It is defined as an arid terrain with clay-rich soil that has been extensively eroded by wind and water. Additionally, "badland" has a broad synonym, which is "barren land," and an exact synonym, "badlands."

A dry valley is the same as something that is an intersection of a valley and something that, at the very least, possesses some quality of being dry. Essentially, a dry valley is a type of valley as well as a type of entity that has some dry quality. The definition of a dry valley is a valley which no longer has water flowing or accumulating over its surface.

Stream valley is a type of valley and also a type of entity that at least has a part of some stream. It is defined as a valley that contains, and has been formed by, a stream. Furthermore, stream valley is the same as an intersection of a valley and an entity that at least has a part of some stream. Additionally, stream valley has related synonyms such as gullie and ravine.

A rocky reef is a type of reef defined as a ridge of rocks, lying near the surface of the sea, which may be visible at low tide but is usually covered by water. It is exactly synonymous with REEF and has narrow synonyms including atoll reef, bank reef, barrier reef, fringing reef, shore reef, and submerged reef. Furthermore, rocky reef has related synonyms such as ledge, reef, reef flat, and reefs.

An ice sheet is a type of glacier that is also a type of entity characterized by some degree of increased size. It is defined as a glacier which covers an area greater than 50,000 square kilometers. In terms of synonyms, an ice sheet is related to various terms including Arctic pack, ICE FIELD, bay ice, continental glacier, continental ice, glacial tongue, ice field, ice mass, island ice, pack ice, polar ice, polar ice pack, rock glacier, and shelf ice.

A glacier is a type of mass composed of compounded environmental materials, primarily consisting of elements such as snow and ice, and it also includes components that are combinations of rock and ice. It plays an active role in the glacial transport process. Defined as an ice mass of sufficient size that gravity's force overcomes the frictional forces holding it in place, leading it to deform and flow towards lower elevations, glaciers are broadly synonymous with the term "glacial feature" and are relatedly synonymous with both "RockGlacier" and "rock glacier."

Permafrost is a type of environmental material that has the qualities of being at least at some decreased temperature. Moreover, it is composed primarily of a combination of rock, soil, and sediment. The definition of permafrost includes it being an environmental material which is primarily composed of soil or rock, including ice or organic material, and remains at or below the freezing point of water for two or more years.

A buffer zone is a type of administrative region defined as a geographical region that serves the purpose of keeping two or more areas (often, but not necessarily, countries) distant from one another, for whatever reason. Additionally, it is related to the synonym "administrative area."

A demilitarized zone is a type of buffer zone, defined as a geographical area, usually the frontier or boundary between two or more military powers (or alliances), where military activity is not permitted. This is typically enforced by a peace treaty, armistice, or other bilateral or multilateral agreement. It is broadly synonymous with an administrative area and has exact synonyms including DEMILITARIZED ZONE, DMZ, and neutral zone. Additionally, it is also related to the concept of a boundary.

A coastal inlet is defined as an opening of the sea into the land, which is synonymous with itself. It is identified as a type of inlet that is at least partially surrounded by some sea coast. Additionally, a coastal inlet is considered the same as an intersection of an inlet and something that is at least part of the union of an ocean and a sea. This definition also clarifies that a coastal inlet is specifically a type of entity that is at least part of the union of an ocean and a sea.
A cove is a type of coastal inlet, which is characterized by having a quality that is at least somewhat circular. Additionally, a cove is defined as a circular or round inlet with a narrow entrance.
An irrigation ditch is a type of ditch that is defined as a ditch that supplies water to surrounding land. It is also broadly synonymous with a canal.
A drainage ditch is a type of ditch defined as a ditch that collects water from the surrounding land. It is also related to and synonymously known as a canal and a rhyne.

A bank is a type of slope and is also a type of something that forms at least part of the channel of a watercourse. It is defined as the sloping margin of a watercourse, serving to confine it to its natural channel. Additionally, "mount" is considered a broad synonym for bank, and "shore" is a related synonym.
A stream bank is a type of bank defined as the sloping margin of a stream, serving to confine it to its natural channel. Additionally, it is related to the synonym "bank (hydrographic)."

River bank, which is a type of stream bank, has the definition of being the sloping margin of a river, serving to confine it to its natural channel. Additionally, river bank has an exact synonym, "riverbank."

An ice cap is a type of land ice mass that is defined as a dome-shaped ice mass covering less than 50,000 km2 of land area, usually covering a highland area. It has an exact synonym, "icecap," and a related synonym, "ice field."

A snow field is a type of field characterized by being a type of entity that, at a minimum, includes a part that is an intersection of an entity that is a surface layer and an entity that is primarily composed of snow. It is defined as a region of permanent snow in mountainous areas or high latitudes. The exact synonyms for snow field are SNOWFIELD and snowfield, while it also has related synonyms SnowField and snowfield.

Ocean currents are defined as the region occupied by any more or less continuous, directed movement of ocean water that flows in one of the Earth's oceans. They are essentially rivers of hot or cold water within the ocean, generated by various forces such as the Earth's rotation, wind, temperature and salinity differences, and the moon's gravitation. Additionally, the depth contours, shoreline, and other movements influence the direction and strength of the water movements that form a given current. Ocean currents are a type of marine current and also a type of phenomenon that is at least part of some ocean. They are synonymous with currents and are the same as something that intersects with marine currents and something that is at least part of some ocean.

Riffle is a type of compound astronomical body part and is also a part of some streams. Additionally, it constitutes something that intersects with hydroform and possesses an irregular thickness. Riffle is defined as a shallow stretch of a river or stream, where the current exceeds the average stream velocity, leading to the formation of small rippled waves. This often occurs over a rocky bed composed of gravels or other small stones.
An artificial reef, which is a type of reef, is defined as chains of rocks or coral at or near the surface of water that are constructed by humans.

A coral reef is a type of marine reef that is defined as a marine reef primarily composed of aragonite structures produced by living organisms, found in shallow, low-nutrient waters. It has an exact synonym, "CoralReef," and is also related to synonyms such as "barrier reef," "fringing reef," and "reef."
Sabkha is a type of alkaline flat, defined as such in the context of a marine environment. It has a broad synonym "basin" and is also relatedly referred to as a "flat."

An anabranch is a type of stream defined as a section of a river or stream that diverts from the main course and rejoins later. It is broadly synonymous with watercourse and is also relatedly referred to as a stream.

Headwater is a compound astronomical body part and is also defined as the upper part of a river system, indicating the upper basin and source streams of a river. It represents something that constitutes at least part of some stream and has a portion of some structural basin. Headwater is broadly synonymous with "stream" and has exact synonyms "HEADWATER" and "headwaters." Additionally, it is related to the terms "drainage basin," "headstream," and "source."

The flood meadow ecosystem, which is a type of wet meadow ecosystem, is defined as an area of grassland or pasture beside a river, subject to seasonal flooding. It is also related to and synonymous with the term water meadow.

A cirque is a type of glacial valley and a type of something that at least formed as a result of some glacial erosion process. It is defined as a depression which is semicircular or crescent-shaped, found towards the crest of a mountain, and formed by the erosional processes caused by the motion of a glacier. Cirque has exact synonyms including cirque basin, cirques, coomb, coombe, corrie, and cwm.

A desert oasis is defined as a small, isolated, fertile, or green area in a desert region, typically featuring a spring or well. It is recognized as a type of oasis and also as a type of area that is at least partly within some desert area. Furthermore, a desert oasis is equivalent to an intersection of an oasis and an area that is at least partly within a desert region.

Peat cut is a type of surface landform and also a type of entity that at least overlaps some peatland. It is defined as an artificial working of peatland to remove the peat. Moreover, peat cut has a broad synonym, wetland, and exact synonyms like peat cutting, along with a related synonym, peat cutting area.

A causeway is a type of transport feature defined as a road or railway elevated by a bank, usually across a broad body of water or wetland. Additionally, causeway is synonymous with both "causeway" and "road."
A sugar plantation is a type of plantation and it is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site.
A sisal plantation is a type of plantation and it is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site.
A banana plantation is a type of plantation and it is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site.
A tea plantation is a type of plantation and is also broadly synonymous with an agricultural site. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, which is tea estate.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:coffee_plantation rdfs:subClassOf :plantation .
text: coffee plantation is a type of plantation.

A rubber plantation is a type of plantation defined as a plantation used to grow Hevea brasiliensis or other species from which natural latex is harvested. It is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site.

An asphalt lake, which is a type of lake, is defined as a lake formed of a natural deposit of asphalt, a black, highly viscous liquid or semi-solid composed of fossil hydrocarbons. It also has a broad synonym, "basin," and an exact synonym, "tar pit."

An atoll is a type of oceanic island that is often characterized by a ring-like shape surrounding a lagoon. It is formed when a coral reef grows around a volcanic island, which then subsides into the ocean. Atoll has a broad synonym of "island" and an exact synonym of "coral atoll." Additionally, it has related synonyms including "REEF," "ISLAND," "atoll," and "reef."

fragment:
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

:bar rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_quality ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :elongated ],
        [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_quality ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :linear ],
        :hydrographic_feature ;
    :has_broad_synonym "seafloor feature"^^xsd:string ;
    :has_definition "A linear shoaling landform feature within a body of water. Bars tend to be long and narrow (linear) and develop where a current (or waves) promote deposition of granular material, resulting in localized shallowing (shoaling) of the water. Bars can appear in the sea, in a lake, or in a river. They are typically composed of sand, although could be of any granular matter that the moving water has access to and is capable of shifting around (for example, soil, silt, gravel, cobble, shingle, or even boulders). The grain size of the material comprising a bar is related: to the size of the waves or the strength of the currents moving the material, but the availability of material to be worked by waves and currents is also important."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "Shoal"^^xsd:string,
        "ball"^^xsd:string,
        "bank"^^xsd:string,
        "barrier beach"^^xsd:string,
        "barrier island"^^xsd:string,
        "cuspate spit"^^xsd:string,
        "hook"^^xsd:string,
        "hooked spit"^^xsd:string,
        "longshore bar"^^xsd:string,
        "marsh bar"^^xsd:string,
        "offshore bar"^^xsd:string,
        "point"^^xsd:string,
        "recurved spit"^^xsd:string,
        "sand bank"^^xsd:string,
        "sand bar"^^xsd:string,
        "sand hom"^^xsd:string,
        "sand lobe"^^xsd:string,
        "sand spit"^^xsd:string,
        "sandbar"^^xsd:string,
        "shoal"^^xsd:string,
        "shoal patches"^^xsd:string,
        "shoals"^^xsd:string,
        "spit"^^xsd:string,
        "tongue"^^xsd:string,
        "tongue (seafloor)"^^xsd:string,
        "transverse bar"^^xsd:string,
        "undersea shoal"^^xsd:string .
text:
Bar is recognized as a type of hydrographic feature, which is characterized by its qualities of being elongated and linear. It is defined as a linear shoaling landform feature within a body of water, such as the sea, a lake, or a river. Bars are typically long and narrow, developing in areas where currents or waves facilitate the deposition of granular material, leading to a localized shallowing of the water. These formations are usually made up of sand but can consist of any granular matter like soil, silt, gravel, cobble, shingle, or boulders, which the moving water can transport. The size of the material making up a bar correlates with the wave size or the strength of the currents moving the material, with the availability of material also playing a crucial role.

Additionally, bar is broadly synonymous with seafloor feature and has a variety of related synonyms that describe similar or related hydrographic features. These include Shoal, Ball, Bank, Barrier Beach, Barrier Island, Cuspate Spit, Hook, Hooked Spit, Longshore Bar, Marsh Bar, Offshore Bar, Point, Recurved Spit, Sand Bank, Sand Bar, Sand Hom, Sand Lobe, Sand Spit, Sandbar, Shoal, Shoal Patches, Shoals, Spit, Tongue, Tongue (Seafloor), Transverse Bar, and Undersea Shoal.

A blowhole is a type of hydrographic feature and also a type of feature that at least overlaps some sea coast. It is defined as a hole in coastal rock through which sea water is forced by a rising tide or waves and spurted through an outlet into the air.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

:canyon rdfs:subClassOf :valley ;
    :has_definition "Relatively narrow, deep depression with steep sides, the bottom of which generally has a continuous slope."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "barranca"^^xsd:string,
        "chasm"^^xsd:string,
        "defile"^^xsd:string,
        "flume (natural)"^^xsd:string,
        "gap"^^xsd:string,
        "gorge"^^xsd:string,
        "gulch"^^xsd:string,
        "quebrada"^^xsd:string,
        "ravine"^^xsd:string,
        "valley"^^xsd:string .
text: A canyon is a type of valley characterized by its relatively narrow, deep depression with steep sides, where the bottom generally has a continuous slope. It shares synonyms with several other geographical terms such as barranca, chasm, defile, flume (natural), gap, gorge, gulch, quebrada, ravine, and valley, indicating a variety of similar natural formations distinguished by specific features.

Dune is a type of hill and something that is at least formed as a result of some aeolian transport process. It is defined as a hill of sand built by eolian processes. Dune has broad synonyms including mount, ridge, and sandy area. Additionally, it has an exact synonym which is sand dune, and a narrow synonym, interdune trough. Furthermore, dune has a related synonym, sand hill.
A river valley is a type of stream valley and also a type of entity that at least has part some river. It is defined as a valley that contains, and has been formed by, a river.
The sandy desert is a type of desert area defined as a desert plain characterized by a surface veneer of sand. It is broadly synonymous with both desert and sandy area.

A rocky desert is a type of desert area, defined as a desert plain characterized by a surface veneer of rock. It is broadly synonymous with the term desert and is exactly synonymous with the term rock desert.

An isthmus is a type of surface landform, defined as a narrow section of land in a body of water connecting two larger land areas. It is also related to synonyms such as land bridge, neck, and submarine isthmus.

Karst is a type of surface landform that is characterized by several key features. It is a type of landform that necessarily includes at least some parts of limestone caves and possesses the quality of eroding. Additionally, karst formation is a result of bedrock dissolution. Karst is defined as a surface landform which is formed by the dissolution of a soluble layer or layers of bedrock. Furthermore, "karst area" is a related synonym to karst.

An elevated landform is the same as something that is an intersection of a landform and something that has at least some increased elevation. It is a type of landform and also a type of entity that has at least a part that is a slope, as well as a type of entity that has at least some quality of increased elevation. An elevated landform is defined as a landform elevated above the surrounding area and has a broad synonym: elevation.

Moraine is a type of surface landform and also a type of entity that is formed as a result of some glacial erosion process. It is defined as an accumulation of boulders, stones, or other debris carried and deposited by a glacier. Furthermore, moraine is exactly synonymous with glacial moraine.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

:levee rdfs:subClassOf :human_construction,
        :hydrographic_feature,
        :slope ;
    :has_definition "An artificial slope or wall, usually earthen, which parallels the course of a river, built for the purpose of containing the river."^^xsd:string ;
    :has_related_synonym "EMBANKMENT"^^xsd:string,
        "REVETMENT"^^xsd:string,
        "berm"^^xsd:string,
        "dike"^^xsd:string,
        "dike (manmade)"^^xsd:string,
        "dyke"^^xsd:string,
        "embankment"^^xsd:string,
        "levee"^^xsd:string,
        "revetment"^^xsd:string .
text: A levee is a type of hydrographic feature, human construction, and slope characterized by being an artificial slope or wall, usually earthen, which parallels the course of a river, built for the purpose of containing the river. It has several related synonyms, including EMBANKMENT, REVETMENT, berm, dike, dike (manmade), dyke, embankment, levee, and revetment.

Mesa is a type of flattened elevation and it is defined as an elevated area of land with a flat top and sides that are usually steep cliffs. Mesas form in areas where horizontally layered rocks are uplifted by tectonic activity. Moreover, mesa has a broad synonym, plateau, and a related synonym, butte.
A mound is a type of mount and is defined as a rounded elevated area. Moreover, mound is related to synonyms such as mound itself and mount.

A nunatak is defined as the exposed summit of a ridge, mountain, or peak not covered with ice or snow within an ice field or glacier, typically used in areas where a permanent ice mass is present. This term is synonymous with a glacier feature and is related to mountain summit, nunatak, nunataks, and peak. Furthermore, a nunatak is both a type of peak and a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some glacier. It represents the intersection of a peak and an entity that is at least adjacent to some glacier.

A plateau is a type of flattened elevation, which is defined as an elevated and comparatively level expanse of land. It has exact synonyms including PLATEAU and Plateau. Additionally, plateau is associated with related synonyms such as highland, intermontane plateau, plateau, table mountain, tableknoll, tableland, tablemount, and upland.
A stony desert is a type of desert area, which is defined as a desert plain characterized by a surface veneer of gravel or stones. It is broadly synonymous with the term desert.

A hanging valley is a type of glacial valley characterized by a tributary valley with the floor at a higher relief than the main channel into which it flows. They are most commonly associated with U-shaped valleys when a tributary glacier flows into a glacier of larger volume. Additionally, "hanging valley" has a broad synonym: "valley."

Raised mire is a type of peatland characterized by being rain-fed, potentially deep peatlands that primarily occur in lowland areas across much of Northern Europe, as well as in the former USSR, North America, and parts of the southern hemisphere. It is broadly synonymous with wetland and is also relatedly known as a raised bog.

A string mire is recognized as a type of peatland, which is broadly synonymous with a wetland and exactly synonymous with a string bog. It is characterized as a type of environment that, at the very least, possesses qualities overlapping some hummock and incorporates at least 3 hummock components. Additionally, it is described as a type of setting that is either concave or flattened. The definition of a string mire elaborates on it as flat or concave peatlands with a string-like pattern of hummocks, which is the reason behind its name. These are primarily found in northern Scandinavia, with occurrences in the western parts of the former USSR and in North America, and a few examples are present in northern Britain.

Tundra mire is a type of peatland that also qualifies as a type of entity overlapping with some permafrost and some tundra ecosystem. It is defined as peatlands characterized by a shallow peat layer, roughly 500 mm thick, and dominated by sedges and grasses. These mires form in permafrost areas, spanning approximately 110,000 to 160,000 km^2 across Alaska, Canada, and the former USSR.

Palsa mire is a type of peatland and is also a type of something that at least overlaps some palsa. It is defined as a peatland typified by characteristic high mounds, each with a permanently frozen core, with wet depressions between the mounds.

Peat swamp is a type of peatland and also falls into a category that at least partially overlaps with some forest ecosystem. It is defined as forested peatlands, which include both rain- and groundwater-fed types, and are commonly found in tropical regions with high rainfall.

An abyssal feature is a type of undersea feature defined as a feature on the ocean floor at a depth of 3500 - 6000 meters. It is related to and synonymously known as Abyssalhill, abyssal hill, and ocean floor feature.

A solid astronomical body part is defined as a part of an astronomical body that is primarily composed of a continuous volume of solid material, which is shaped by one or more environmental processes. This is synonymous with terms such as geological feature, landform, and physiographic feature. Additionally, a solid astronomical body part is identified as the same as something that intersects with an astronomical body part and something that is at least primarily composed of solid environmental material. It is categorized as a type of compound astronomical body part and also as a type of entity that is at least primarily composed of solid environmental material.

A mudflat is a type of coastal wetland ecosystem, which is defined as a wetland that forms when mud is deposited by tides, rivers, the sea, or oceans. It is broadly synonymous with the term "wetland" and has "mud flat" as both an exact and related synonym.
An olive grove is a type of plantation, which has related synonyms including "olive grove" itself and "wood."

Scree is defined as broken rock that appears at the bottom of crags, mountain cliffs, or valley shoulders, and it is synonymous with both talus and talus slope. It is identified as a type of environmental material that intersects with materials that have at least some part of a piece of rock and those that at least derive from some rock. This indicates that scree is not only a specific kind of environmental material but also inherently connected to rocks, both in terms of being partially composed of rock pieces and deriving from rock.

A sinkhole is a type of depressed and surface landform, characterized by a natural depression or hole in the surface topography. This occurs due to the removal of soil or bedrock, often both, by water. Sinkholes can range in size from less than a meter to several hundred meters, both in diameter and depth, and vary in form from soil-lined bowls to bedrock-edged chasms. Furthermore, "basin" is considered a broad synonym for sinkhole, while "cenote" and "sink" are related synonyms.

An alkaline flat is a type of dry lake bed, defined as a dry lakebed consisting of fine-grained sediments infused with alkali salts, generally the shore or bed of an endorheic lake. It is related to several synonyms including chott, kavir, playa, and salina.

An endorheic lake is a type of lake that is at least adjacent to some endorheic basin. It is defined as a lake from which there is no outflow of water, either on the surface as rivers or underground by flow or diffusion through rock or permeable material. Additionally, an endorheic lake has an exact synonym: closed lake.
An ice-covered lake, defined as a lake permanently covered by ice, is a type of glacial lake.
A meromictic lake is a type of lake characterized by layers of water that do not intermix, making it distinct from a holomictic lake.
A periglacial lake, which is a type of glacial lake, is defined as a lake part of whose margin is formed by an ice mass, ice cap, or glacier. This ice obstructs the natural drainage of the land.
A fjord lake is a type of lake and is also a type of entity that is at least located in some fjord. It is defined as a lake in a glacially eroded valley, which has been eroded below sea level.

An oxbow lake is a type of lake characterized by a unique formation process. It is formed when a wide meander from a stream or a river is cut off, creating a lake. This process gives it a distinctive curved shape, which is why they are called oxbow lakes.

A rift lake is a type of tectonic lake and also a type of entity that, at the very least, formed as a result of some divergent tectonic movement. It is defined as a lake which fills a depression that has formed as a result of subsidence along a rift zone, an area of extensional tectonics in the continental crust.
Ephemeral spring is a type of spring characterized by intermittent fluid flow, meaning fluid flows through it occasionally.
A permanent spring is a type of spring characterized by a continuous flow.
The marine neritic zone is a type of marine layer that is disjoint with the oceanic zone. It is defined as the water mass of an ocean directly above a continental shelf.

The oceanic zone is a type of marine layer and is considered a part of the ocean that is not above a continental shelf. Moreover, it is also referred to as the OceanLayer. This zone is defined as the water mass of an ocean.
The marine pelagic zone is a type of marine layer characterized by being an open ocean region.

The marine photic zone is a type of marine layer, and it's also a part of a planetary photic zone. It is defined as the zone of an ocean from the surface to where photosynthesis can occur, due to the penetration of light. Moreover, the marine photic zone is exactly synonymous with both PhoticZone and the epipelagic zone.

The marine aphotic zone is a type of marine layer, defined as the zone of an ocean below 200m where photosynthesis cannot occur due to the lack of light. It is also exactly synonymous with AphoticZone.
The marine bathypelagic zone, a type of marine aphotic zone, is defined as the part of an ocean below the 10°C thermocline down to a temperature of 4°C.
The marine abyssalpelagic zone is a type of marine aphotic zone, defined as the zone of the ocean below the bathypelagic zone, with its lowest boundary at about 6000 meters.

The marine mesopelagic zone, which is a type of marine aphotic zone, is defined as the zone of an ocean immediately below the photic zone, extending down to a depth where the water temperature reaches 10°C, known as the thermocline.
The hadalpelagic zone, a type of marine aphotic zone, is defined as the zone of an ocean in oceanic trenches, lying between 6,000m and 10,000m.
A hydrothermal vent is a type of spring that serves as a fissure in the Earth's surface from which geothermally heated water issues. It is also exactly synonymous with HydrothermalVents.

A fumarole is a type of geological fracture defined as a hole in the Earth's crust from which steam and gases are emitted. It is broadly synonymous with a thermal feature and has an exact synonym, FUMAROLE.
Solfatara is a type of fumarole, characterized by being a fumarole that emits sulfurous gases.

A black smoker is a type of marine hydrothermal vent found on the ocean floor. These vents are formed in fields hundreds of meters wide when superheated water from below the Earth's crust comes through the ocean floor. The superheated water is rich in dissolved minerals from the crust, most notably sulfides, which crystallize to create a chimney-like structure around each vent. When the superheated water in the vent comes in contact with the cold ocean water, many minerals are precipitated, creating the distinctive black color. The metal sulfides that are deposited can become massive sulfide ore deposits in time. Black smokers are also known by the exact synonym "active chimney" and are related to "oceanic vent" and "sea vent".

A landlocked sea is a type of sea that is not connected with an ocean, defined as a sea that is disconnected from the ocean. It has a broad synonym "lake" and is also related to the synonym "inland sea."

An archipelago is a type of compound astronomical body part and is also characterized as something that includes at least one island as part of its composition. It is defined as a group of geographically or geologically associated islands. Furthermore, "ISLAND CLUSTER" is an exact synonym for archipelago. Additionally, archipelago is relatedly synonymous with "IslandArc," "island arc," and "island group."

A continental island is a type of island that is the same as something that intersects an island and something that is at least part of some continental shelf. It is also regarded as a type of something that is at least part of some continental shelf. Moreover, a continental island is defined as an island that lies on a continental shelf.

An oceanic island is a type of island that is disconnected from the continental shelf and is characterized as being of volcanic origin, typically formed as a result of volcanic eruptions. It is defined as an island that does not sit on a continental shelf. Additionally, oceanic island has a related synonym, which is volcanic island.

The continental shelf is identified as a type of slope that is part of, or at least overlaps, some continental margin and crust. It is also adjacent to the continental slope. The definition of a continental shelf includes a slope which extends the perimeter of a continent, is covered by a shallow marine water body during interglacial periods, and has a low degree of steepness relative to a continental slope or rise. In terms of terminology, "shelf" is a broad synonym for the continental shelf, while exact synonyms include "shelves" and "continental." Related synonyms encompass "borderland," "borderland (continental margin)," "platform (continental margin)," and "shelf edge (ocean)."

A slightly stratified estuary is a type of estuary defined as one in which the river output is less than the marine input. This situation results in the mixing of the whole water column by current-induced turbulence, leading to a salinity variation that is more longitudinal rather than vertical. Additionally, a slightly stratified estuary is exactly synonymous with both a partially mixed estuary and a vertically mixed estuary.

A highly stratified estuary is a type of estuary defined as an estuary whose river output and marine input are more even, with river flow still dominant; turbulence induces more mixing of salt water upward than the reverse.

A saline wedge estuary, also known as a salt wedge estuary, is a type of estuary characterized by a situation where the river output greatly exceeds marine input. This leads to minimal mixing, thus creating a sharp contrast between the fresh surface water and the saline bottom water.

An inverse estuary is a specific type of estuary characterized by its unique location in regions where evaporation significantly outpaces the inflow of fresh water. This results in a zone of maximum salinity towards which both riverine and marine water masses flow. After converging, these waters sink and spread along the bottom, extending both seaward and landward.

An intermittent estuary is a type of estuary defined by its dramatic variations in volume due to intermittent freshwater input. This capability allows it to change from a wholly marine embayment to any other type of estuary.

A coastal wetland ecosystem is defined as a wetland ecosystem which overlaps both terrestrial and marine ecosystems. It is identified as the intersection of a wetland ecosystem and an area that at least overlaps some sea coast. Furthermore, a coastal wetland ecosystem is classified as a type of wetland ecosystem and also as a type that overlaps with some part of the sea coast.
Moor is a type of freshwater wetland ecosystem and it is defined as a wetland found in upland areas, characterized by acidic soils. Additionally, "moor" is broadly synonymous with itself.

Fen is a type of peatland and also a type of wetland, broadly speaking. It is characterized by being a type of area that, at the very least, contains some fresh water and intersects with areas that contain groundwater and have at least some alkaline quality. Moreover, a fen is defined as a freshwater peatland with chemically basic (which roughly means alkaline) groundwater.

The swamp ecosystem, which is a type of wetland ecosystem, is defined as a wetland ecosystem where the land mass is permanently inundated by shallow bodies of water, typically featuring a significant number of hummocks or dry-land protrusions. It is broadly synonymous with wetland and has exact synonyms such as "Swamp" and "swamp." Additionally, it is related to the term "cienaga."

A bayou is a type of stream defined as a small, slow-moving stream or creek, usually located in low-lying areas. It has broad synonyms such as lake and watercourse. Additionally, bayou is synonymously related to terms like bahia, embayment, lake, and slough.
Carr is a type of fen and it is defined as a fen which has developed to the point where it supports trees.

Dambo is a type of freshwater wetland ecosystem, defined as a class of complex shallow wetlands in central, southern, and eastern Africa, particularly in Zambia and Zimbabwe. They are generally found in higher rainfall flat plateau areas and have river-like branching forms which may be nowhere very large, but common enough to add up to a large area.
A hydromorphic phreatic dambo, which is a type of dambo, is defined as a dambo associated with a headwater.
A fluvial dambo is a type of dambo defined as a dambo associated with a river.

Pocasin is a type of freshwater wetland ecosystem and has a definition as a palustrine wetland with deep, acidic, sandy, peat soils. Groundwater saturates the soil except during brief seasonal dry spells and during prolonged droughts. Moreover, Pocosin soils are nutrient deficient (oligotrophic), especially in phosphorus.

A saline wetland is a type of wetland ecosystem characterized by being a type of entity that contains, at least in part, some saline water. It is defined as a wetland ecosystem in which the soil is saturated with saline water.

A tidal mudflat is a type of mudflat defined as a level tract lying at a small depth below the surface of water, or alternately covered and left bare by the tide. It has a broad synonym, wetland, and exact synonyms, which include FLAT and tidal flat.
A lacustrine mudflat is a type of mudflat defined as a wetland that forms when mud is deposited by a stream.

A freshwater wetland ecosystem is defined as a wetland inundated with water that contains low concentrations of salts. It is identified as a type of wetland ecosystem and falls under several specific categories: it is part of ecosystems that have at least some water body and are primarily composed of fresh water; it is also categorized under ecosystems that are not primarily composed of materials with increased osmolarity or higher levels of sodium chloride, distinguishing it from environments with higher salt content. Moreover, a freshwater wetland ecosystem is described as an ecosystem that intersects with planetary landmasses and is primarily composed of soil and fresh water. This definition encapsulates the essence of a freshwater wetland ecosystem by highlighting its low salt water composition and its relationship with both water bodies and landmasses, emphasizing its distinct ecological characteristics compared to other wetland types.

An abyssal plain is a type of plain that is at least continuous with some ocean floor, representing flat or very gently sloping areas of the deep ocean basin floor. Additionally, it has an exact synonym "Abyssalplain" and a related synonym "abyssal feature."

Maar is a type of crater that has a specific definition. It is described as a broad, low relief crater resulting from a phreatic eruption or explosion caused by groundwater coming into contact with hot lava or magma. Typically, the maar fills with water to form a relatively shallow crater lake.

A volcanic crater is a type of crater that is formed as a result of a volcanic eruption. It is defined as a crater created by a volcano, within which there is a vent (or vents) from which magma erupts as gases, lava, and ejecta. Additionally, "crater" is a related synonym to a volcanic crater.

A volcano is a type of geological fracture and is also a type of entity that is at least formed as a result of some volcanic eruption. It is defined as an opening, or rupture, in the Earth's surface or crust, which allows hot, molten rock, ash, and gases to escape from deep below the surface. Additionally, volcano has a broad synonym, which is mount.

A glacial valley is a type of valley that is defined as a valley that contains, or contained, a glacier and was formed by glacial activity. It is typically U-shaped in cross-section. Furthermore, a glacial valley is related to the synonym "valley."

Lateral moraine is a type of moraine defined as the parallel ridges of till deposited along the sides of a glacier. This unconsolidated debris is deposited on top of the glacier by frost shattering of the valley walls and from tributary streams flowing into the valley. The till is carried along the glacial margin until the glacier melts. Additionally, lateral moraine is broadly synonymous with moraine.
A medial moraine is a type of moraine defined as a moraine formed when the inside lateral moraines of two glaciers merge together, forming a ridge down the center of the combined glaciers.

Ground moraine is a type of moraine that is defined as a till-covered area with irregular topography and no ridges, often forming gently rolling hills or plains. It forms by the accumulation of till under the ice by lodgement but may also be deposited as the glacier retreats.

Terminal moraine, a type of moraine, is defined as ridges of unconsolidated debris deposited at the snout or end of the glacier, usually reflecting the shape of the glacier's terminus. It is exactly synonymous with "end moraine" and is relatedly synonymous with both "delta moraine" and "moraine."

A scroll plane is a type of plain characterized by a specific definition. It is described as a plain where a stream meanders across an area with a very low gradient, typically featuring a fairly continuous discharge. Notably, scroll plains are distinguished not only by their meandering streams but also by the presence of many oxbow lakes.

A till plain is a type of plain that is defined as an extensive flat plain of glacial till. It forms when a sheet of ice becomes detached from the main body of a glacier and melts in place, depositing the sediments it carried.

A flood plain is a type of plain characterized by being an area subject to periodic flooding. It is exactly synonymous with FLOOD PLAIN, Floodplain, and floodplain, and is also relatedly synonymous with bottomland.

A floodway is a type of landform that is characterized as being depressed and a part of the surface landform category. It is also defined as part of at least some portion of a flood plain. Specifically, a floodway has the definition of being the stream channel and adjacent areas that carry flood flows in a flood plain.

Flood fringe is a type of field, and it is a type of something that at least part of some flood plain and at least partially surrounded by some flood. The definition of flood fringe is an area of a flood plain that is covered by the flood but does not experience a strong current.

An alluvial plain is a type of plain characterized by its composition primarily of alluvial soil. It is situated adjacent to or at the intersection of a range of mountains and is notably not associated with seamounts. This landform is defined as a relatively flat and gently sloping area found at the base of a range of hills or mountains. The formation of an alluvial plain is attributed to the long-term deposition of alluvial soil by one or more streams emanating from the mountains.

A lacustrine plain is a type of plain characterized by its origin in a lacustrine environment, specifically as the bed of a lake from which the water has disappeared. This disappearance of water may occur through natural drainage, evaporation, or other geophysical processes.

Prairie is a type of grassland area defined as an area of land of low topographic relief that historically supported grasses and herbs, with few trees, and having generally a mesic (moderate or temperate) climate. It is dominated by tall grasses, contrasting with steppe. Moreover, prairie is synonymously related to several other terms including grassland, llanos, pampa, plain, and veld.

Savanna is a type of grassland area and is defined as a grassland of the tropics or subtropics with scattered trees. It has the exact synonym "Savanna" and is also relatedly synonymous with "grassland" and "savannah."

A steppe is a type of grassland area characterized as a plain without trees, except for those near rivers and lakes. It is similar to a prairie, with the distinction that a prairie typically has tall grasses, whereas short grasses are considered normal in the steppe. The steppe may vary in appearance, being semi-desert, or covered with grass or shrubs or both, which depends on the season and latitude. Additionally, the steppe is synonymously related to grassland, and it is also referred to as pampa, pampas, and puszta.

A fissure cave is a type of cave that is at least continuous with some geological fracture, indicating it is a specific kind of formation. It is defined as a narrow, vertical cave passage, which is often developed along a joint but not necessarily always. The formation of a fissure cave is usually attributed to solution processes, but sometimes it can also result from tension.

A seamount is a type of mountain that is surrounded by an environment where the planetary crust intersects with the combined areas of the ocean and sea. It is defined as a mountain rising from the ocean seafloor that does not reach the water's surface (sea level), and thus is not an island. Typically, seamounts are formed from volcanoes that rise abruptly and are usually found rising from a seafloor with depths ranging from 1,000 to 4,000 meters. They are independent features that rise to at least 1,000 meters above the seafloor. Seamounts have a broad synonym, "mount," and exact synonyms including "mountains," "sea mount," "sea-mount," "seaknoll," and "submarine volcano." Additionally, they have related synonyms such as "hill," "hills," "knoll," "knolls," "mesa," "mound," "mount," "mountain," "peak," "peaks," "range," "seakpeak," "undersea hill," "undersea knoll," and "undersea mound."

A guyot is a type of seamount that is characterized as a flat-topped seamount with at least a part that is an intersection of a peak and something that has a quality of being flattened. It is defined as a flat-topped seamount, and it is broadly synonymous with seamounts. Guyot has exact synonyms including tablemount and tablemounts, and it has related synonyms such as plateau and tablemount (seafloor).

Pasture is a type of agricultural ecosystem, as well as a type of grassland ecosystem. It is also defined as a type of entity that is part of or participates in some agricultural process, specifically as part of a farm or ranch. Furthermore, pasture is defined as a grassland ecosystem used for the grazing of ungulate livestock as part of a farm or ranch. Additionally, pasture is synonymously related to a grazing area.

A submarine canyon is a type of canyon that is situated adjacent to areas that are a combination of the ocean floor and sea floor. It is defined as a steep-sided valley on the sea floor of the continental slope. Notably, many submarine canyons serve as extensions to large rivers, although there are numerous canyons without such associations. These canyons, which carve through the continental slopes, have been discovered at depths greater than 2 kilometers below sea level. Furthermore, many submarine canyons continue as submarine channels across continental rise areas and may extend for hundreds of kilometers. In terms of terminology, "submarine canyon" is broadly synonymous with "canyon" and "canyons," and it has the exact synonyms "SubmarineCanyon" and "undersea canyon." Additionally, "undersea ravine" is considered a related synonym.

A lake bed, which is a type of submerged bed and also something that is at least adjacent to some lake, is defined as the ground surface that lies beneath a lake. Furthermore, "lake bottom" is an exact synonym for lake bed, and "lake" is considered a related synonym.

A land-tied island is a type of continental island, which is defined as a continental island connected to its adjacent land by a natural feature, such as a causeway. It is broadly synonymous with the term "island" and is also relatedly known as a "land-tied island."

A beaver pond is a type of pond defined as a pond that has formed as a consequence of the activities of beavers, specifically through the building of a beaver dam. Additionally, it is synonymously related to a lake.

Chott, also known exactly as shott, is a type of alkaline flat. It is defined as a dry (salt) lake in the Saharan area of Africa that remains dry in the summer but receives some water in the winter, which may come as a groundwater discharge.

Confluence is a type of hydrographic feature and is also considered a type of element that constitutes at least part of a stream.
