It is defined as the point where a tributary joins a more major river. Moreover, confluence is broadly synonymous with stream and is relatedly synonymous with stream junction.

The continental slope is a type of slope that forms part of the continental margin and is adjacent to the continental shelf. It is defined as a slope which is part of the seafloor and extends from the end of the continental shelf (the shelf break) to the continental rise.

Continental rise is a type of slope that is part of at least some continental margin and is adjacent to both an abyssal plain and a continental slope. It is defined as a slope which bridges and thus lies between a continental slope and an abyssal plain. It is formed by the accumulation of sediments transported from a continental slope by processes including turbidity currents. Additionally, the gradient of a continental rise is less than that of a continental slope yet greater than that of a continental shelf.

An ocean trench is a type of trench that is at least partly adjacent to an ocean and is located on the ocean or sea floor. These trenches are hemispheric-scale long but narrow topographic depressions of the sea floor and are known to be the deepest parts of the ocean floor. Ocean trench is exactly synonymous with "Trench" and "deep sea trench," and is relatedly synonymous with "deep" and "undersea trench."

A drumlin is a type of hill defined as an elongated whale-shaped hill formed by glacial action. Its long axis is parallel to the movement of the ice, with the blunter end facing into the glacial movement. Unlike kames, whose formation differs significantly, a drumlin is not shaped by meltwater but by the ice itself and showcases a quite regular shape. It typically occurs in fine-grained material, such as clay or shale, rather than in sands and gravels, and usually features concentric layers of material, as the ice successively plasters new layers in its movement. Furthermore, drumlin is related to the synonyms "mount" and "ridge."

Dry lake is a type of landform that is both depressed and a surface landform. It is defined as a lake that has either permanently or temporally lost its water. Additionally, dry lake is broadly synonymous with lake and is relatedly synonymous with lake bed.

A dry stream is a type of channel of a watercourse that has the quality of being at least somewhat dry. It is defined as a stream channel through which no water flows and which has dried, containing no appreciable accumulations of water. Additionally, the term "dry stream bed" is a related synonym to dry stream.

A saline pan, also known as a salt pan, is a type of dry lake bed. It is defined as a flat expanse of ground covered with salt and other minerals, typically shining white under the sun. Such formations occur where water pools but cannot drain into the ground and remains on the surface until it evaporates, leaving behind dissolved minerals. Over thousands of years, these minerals, usually salts, accumulate on the surface. A saline pan would exist as a lake or a pond if it were not located in a desert, where the rate of water evaporation surpasses the rate of water precipitation. Saline pans are also referred to by related synonyms such as salt area and salt flat.

An escarpment is a type of slope that forms as a result of the union of tectonic movement and erosion. It is primarily composed of sedimentary rock. An escarpment, also known as a scarp, separates different physiogeographic provinces that are typically composed of rocks of different age and composition. Besides being exactly synonymous with "scarp," an escarpment is also relatedly synonymous with "cliff" and "cuesta."
A fault escarpment is a type of escarpment and is something that is at least formed as a result of some tectonic movement. It is defined as an escarpment resulting from a fault.

Esker is a type of ridge and has the definition of being a long, winding ridge of stratified sand and gravel which occurs in glaciated and formerly glaciated regions of Europe and North America. Furthermore, esker is related to the synonym "ridge."

A ridge is a type of elevated landform that is characterized by having at least some decreased thickness and being somewhat elongated. It is defined as a long and narrow elevation with steep sides. The term "ridge" has exact synonyms, including "RIDGE" and "Ridge." Additionally, more specific types of ridges are referred to as beach cusp, beach ridge, icecap ridge, and rise (seafloor), which are considered narrow synonyms. Related terms that are somewhat synonymous with ridge include arete, crest, cuesta, hogback, ridge, spur, and spur (physiographic), reflecting the variety of forms and contexts in which ridges occur.

A quarry is defined as an open-pit mine from which rock or minerals are extracted. It is characterized as being the same as an entity that is both an open pit mine and capable of a process that involves the intersection of material extraction and the production of rock. Additionally, a quarry is identified as a type of open pit mine and also as a type that is at least capable of a material extraction process that results in the output of rock.
A quicksand bed is a type of surface layer and is primarily composed of quicksand. It is defined as a bed composed of quicksand forming a soft, shifting mass that yields easily to pressure.
A polder is a type of surface landform and has a definition as an area reclaimed from the sea by diking and draining. Moreover, it is broadly synonymous with the physiographic feature.

A butte is a type of flattened elevation, defined as an isolated hill with steep sides and a small flat top, which is smaller than mesas and plateaus. The formation of buttes occurs through erosion when a cap of hard rock, usually of volcanic origin, covers a layer of softer rock that is easily worn away, allowing the hard rock to avoid erosion while the surrounding rock wears down. Additionally, butte is broadly synonymous with plateau.
A cotton plantation is a type of plantation and it is broadly synonymous with an agricultural site.

Horst is a type of elevated and surface landform. It is defined as the raised fault block bounded by normal faults, which is a portion of the Earth's crust that has remained stationary while the land has sunk on either side of it or has been crushed by a mountain range against it.

Graben is a type of depressed and surface landform, defined as a depressed block of land bordered by parallel faults. It is the result of a block of land being downthrown, producing a valley with a distinct scarp on each side. Grabens often occur side-by-side with horsts, and both horst and graben structures are indicative of tensional forces and crustal stretching. Additionally, graben is related to the synonym "fault zone."

A drainage basin is a type of landform that is both depressed and surface. It is defined as an extent or area of land where surface water from rain and melting snow or ice converges to a single point at lower elevation, usually the exit of the basin, where the waters join another waterbody. The term "drainage basin" is exactly synonymous with "Basin" and has related synonyms such as "CATCHMENT," "Catchment," "Watershed," "catchment," "drainage basin," and "watershed."

A watershed, which is a type of solid astronomical body part, is defined as the separation between neighboring drainage basins (catchments). In hilly country, the watershed is found along topographical peaks and ridges. However, in flat country or on a high plateau, especially where the ground is marshy, the watershed may be invisible, essentially being just a more or less notional line on the ground. On either side of this line, falling raindrops will start a journey to different rivers, and even to different sides of a country or continent. Watershed is exactly synonymous with "divide" and "water divide." Additionally, it has related synonyms such as "ridge line," "divide," and "drainage basin."

A continental divide is a type of watershed characterized by the following definition: it is a watershed such that water falling on one side of the line eventually travels to one ocean or body of water, and water on the other side travels to another, generally on the opposite side of the continent.

A fish farm is a type of agricultural ecosystem and is defined as a facility in which fish are raised commercially in tanks or enclosures, usually for food. Additionally, it is related to the synonym aquacultural site and also known as a fishery.
A fish hatchery is a type of hatchery with the definition of being a facility where the eggs of fish are hatched under artificial conditions.
A rice field is a type of plantation, defined as a paddy field for the cultivation of rice. It is also related to and synonymously referred to as an agricultural site, cropland, and rice paddy.
A paddy field is a type of agricultural field defined as a flooded parcel of arable land used for growing rice and other semiaquatic crops.

Marine iceberg is a type of floating ice mass and is also known as a type of iceberg. It is defined as a large mass of detached land ice in the sea or stranded in shallow water. The term 'marine iceberg' has an exact synonym, ICEBERG. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as Iceberg, arched iceberg, glacial berg, and glacial iceberg.

An ice field is a type of field, cryoform, and something that is at least composed primarily of water ice. It is defined as a field of ice, formed in regions of perennial frost. Ice field has narrow synonyms including ice patch, iceberg, and icefall. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as IceSheet, ice field, ice sheet, and icecap.

A scrubland area is a type of vegetated area defined as an area covered with low-growing or stunted perennial vegetation and usually not mixed with trees. It has an exact synonym, scrubland. Additionally, it has related synonyms including bush, chaparral area, heath, scrub, and shrubland.

Chaparral area is defined as a type of scrubland area that intersects with regions possessing at least some Mediterranean qualities. Specifically, it is a shrubland area primarily found in regions with a Mediterranean climate, characterized by mild, wet winters and hot, dry summers, and often shaped by wildfires. Additionally, chaparral area is synonymous with chaparal area, maquis, and woodland, highlighting its diverse nomenclature across different regions.

A rift valley is a type of valley that is specifically formed as a result of divergent tectonic movements. It is defined as a valley created by the formation of a rift, which is a place where a planet's lithosphere is being pulled apart by tectonic forces. Additionally, rift valley is related to the synonyms RiftValley and rift zone.

A sea coast is a type of coast that at least overlaps with something that is a union of something that is an ocean and a sea. It is defined as the general region of indefinite width that extends from the sea inland to the first major change in terrain features. Additionally, sea coast is related to synonyms such as coastline, coastal area, and coast line.

Shore is identified as a type of surface landform, which is also recognized as a component of a coast or as something adjacent to a water body. It is defined as that part of the land in immediate contact with a body of water, including the area between high and low water lines. The term "shore" is broadly synonymous with "coastal zone" and has more specific synonyms, including "shoreface." Additionally, related synonyms for shore encompass "beach face," "foreshore," "inshore," "rivage," "seashore," and "strand."

A peninsula is a type of part of a landmass and a surface landform, characterized by protruding out of its surroundings and being adjacent to a water body. It is defined as a body of land jutting out into and nearly surrounded by water. Related synonyms for peninsula include cape, foreland, head, headland, hook, neck, ness, point, point (physiographic), points, promontory, promontgory, tongue, and winged headland.

Spit is a type of bar that is defined as a deposition landform found off coasts. Specifically, a spit is a bar or beach that develops where a re-entrant occurs, such as at a cove, bay, ria, or river mouth. They are formed by the movement of sediment (typically sand) along a shore through a process known as longshore drift. When the direction of the shore turns inland (reenters), the longshore current spreads out or dissipates, unable to carry the full load of sediment, much of which is dropped. This results in a bar building out from the shore, eventually becoming a spit. Additionally, spit is related to the synonym bar and also has spit as a related synonym.

Icefall is a type of land ice mass and is considered a part of a glacier, featuring at least some portion of a crevasse. It is defined as a portion of a glacier characterized by rapid flow, a chaotic crevassed surface, and a pronounced, at times vertical, slope. Additionally, icefall has exact synonyms: "ice fall" and "ice-fall".
A dune slack is a type of valley, specifically defined as a valley or trough between two dunes. It is also exactly synonymous with an interdune trough.

A depressed landform is defined as a landform sunken or depressed below the surrounding area, which is synonymous with being a type of landform that intersects with landforms having at least some decreased elevation. This kind of landform is characterized by having at least a part that is a slope, showcasing qualities of decreased elevation, and being sloped downward. Depressed landforms are broadly synonymous with the term "depression" and have related synonyms including barrier basin, non-tidal basin, pan, pan (geologic), pans, and tidal basin.

A meteor impact crater is a type of impact crater and also a type of formation that results at least from the impact of a meteorite. It is defined as a crater caused by the impact of a meteor. Additionally, meteor impact crater has exact synonyms, including meteorite crater, meteorite impact crater, and meteoroid impact crater.

Kettle is categorized as a type of depressed and surface landform, and it is part of, at least to some extent, a sandur. It is defined as a fluvioglacial landform that forms when blocks of ice calve from the front of a receding glacier and become partially to wholly buried by glacial outwash. This glacial outwash is created when streams of meltwater, laden with sediment, flow away from the glacier, depositing material to form broad outwash plains known as sandurs. As the ice blocks melt, holes are left in the sandur. Additionally, kettle is broadly synonymous with basin and has an exact synonym, kettle hole.

A sandur is a type of plain characterized by the large amounts of silt and sediment it is formed from. This sediment is picked up as a glacier erodes the underlying rocks while moving slowly downhill. At the glacier's snout, meltwater carries this sediment away from the glacier and deposits it on a broad plain. The material in the sandur is often size-sorted by the water runoff of the melting glacier, with the finest materials, like silt, being the most distantly re-deposited, whereas larger boulders are found closest to the original terminus of the glacier. Additionally, sandur has a related synonym: outwash plain.
Blowout is a type of depressed and surface landform, defined as a sandy depression in a sand dune ecosystem (psammosere) caused by the removal of sediments by wind.

An alluvial fan is defined as a fan-shaped deposit formed where a fast-flowing stream flattens, slows, and spreads, typically at the exit of a canyon onto a flatter plain. It is synonymous with "fan (alluvial)" and is also related to the term "fan." This hydrographic feature is characterized by intersecting qualities such as having a fan shape, being adjacent to an alluvial plain, being an output of a depositional process, and being primarily composed of alluvial soil. Thus, an alluvial fan is a specific type of entity that not only shares these attributes but also specifically qualifies as a hydrographic feature with these interconnected characteristics.

Bajada is a type of alluvial fan and has a definition as a convergence of neighboring alluvial fans into a single apron of deposits against a slope. Additionally, bajada is synonymously related to the term desert.

The intertidal zone is a type of marine environmental zone that encompasses at least part of some shores and overlaps with some intertidal ecosystems. It is defined as the area of the foreshore and seabed that is exposed to the air at low tide and submerged at high tide, i.e., the area between tide marks. This zone is broadly synonymous with the coastal zone and has an exact synonym, IntertidalZone. Additionally, it is related to the littoral zone.

A tidal pool is a type of lentic water body and is also a type of entity that is at least located in some intertidal zone. It is defined as pools formed when a high tide comes in over a rocky shore. Water fills depressions in the ground, which turn into isolated pools as the tide retreats.

The high tide zone is a type of marine environmental zone and also a part of the intertidal zone that is flooded during high tide only. It is characterized as a highly saline environment. Additionally, the high tide zone is synonymously referred to as the upper littoral.

The low tide zone is a type of marine environmental zone and is considered a part of some intertidal zone, at least partially. It is defined as the tidal zone that is mostly submerged, only being exposed at the point of low tide and for a longer period of time during extremely low tides. Additionally, it is synonymously related to the term "lower littoral."

A crevasse is a type of geological fracture and is specifically defined as a deep fissure in snow or ice. It is a type of formation that is at least located in some environment characterized by a union of water ice and snow. Additionally, a crevasse is exactly synonymous with CREVASSE and has related synonyms such as cleft and fissure. Importantly, a crevasse is disjoint with a crevice, indicating a clear distinction between the two.
A joint plane cave is a type of cave that is defined as a cavity developed along a joint and elongate in cross-section.
A volcanic cave is a type of primary cave that is formed in volcanic rock. Additionally, it is synonymously related to a lava cave.
A live cave is a type of cave defined as a cave containing a stream or active speleothems.

An outflow cave is a type of cave characterized by the presence of a stream that flows from it or formerly did so, and it is distinguished by the fact that it cannot be followed upstream to the surface.

Polje is a type of depressed, surface landform and is characterized by having at least some closed quality. It is defined as a large closed depression that drains underground, featuring a flat floor across which there may be an intermittent or perennial stream. This landform may be susceptible to flooding, potentially becoming a lake, and its floor sharply contrasts with parts of the surrounding slopes.
A sea cave is a type of cave characterized by its location in present-day or emerged sea cliffs, formed through processes such as wave attack or solution.
A speleothem is a type of mineral deposit and a type of something that is at least part of some cave. It is defined as a secondary mineral deposit formed in caves, most commonly calcite.

The vadose zone is a type of environmental zone defined as a zone beneath the land surface and above the level of permanent groundwater or phreatic zone, where water has a hydraulic head less than atmospheric pressure and is retained by a combination of adhesion and capillary action. This zone is also precisely known as the unsaturated zone.

The Phreatic Zone is a type of compound astronomical body part, which is also known for being a part of the environment where groundwater is present. It is specifically identified as the part where there is an intersection between solid environmental material and materials that possess a porous quality. The Phreatic Zone is defined as a compound astronomical body part located beneath the land surface, where all interstices are filled with water that has a hydraulic head greater than atmospheric pressure, attributed to the weight of overlying groundwater. Additionally, it is synonymously related to the zone of saturation.
A stalagmite, which is a type of speleothem, is defined as a speleothem projecting vertically upwards from a cave floor and formed by precipitation from drips.
A stalactite is a type of speleothem defined as a speleothem hanging downwards from a roof or wall, of cylindrical or conical form, usually with a central hollow tube.

Doline is a type of depressed landform and also a type of subsurface landform, which is part of some karst. It is defined as a closed depression draining underground in karst, characterized by a simple but variable form that can be cylindrical, conical, bowl- or dish-shaped, ranging in size from a few to many hundreds of meters in dimensions.
Subjacent karst is a type of karst that is defined as karst developed in soluble beds underlying other rock formations; the surface may or may not be affected by the karst development.
Syngenetic karst is a type of karst defined as karst developed in eolian calcarenite when the development of karst features has taken place concurrently with the lithification of dune sand.
Polygonal karst is a type of karst that is defined by being completely pitted by closed depressions, so that the divides between them form a crudely polygonal network.

Doline karst is defined as karst dominated by closed depressions, chiefly dolines, perforating a simple surface. It is a type of karst that is characterized as being the same as the intersection of karst and something that, at a minimum, includes some part of a doline. Moreover, doline karst is specifically a type of entity that has at least a portion consisting of dolines.

Vomit material is defined as a bodily fluid material that is primarily composed of vomit, which itself is a bodily fluid consisting of the expelled contents of an organism's stomach, disgorged through the mouth or nose.

A piece of rock is defined as a mass of solid material which is composed primarily of rock. It is categorized as a type of mass of solid material and is also classified as a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of some rock. Furthermore, a piece of rock is considered the same as something that intersects the categories of mass of solid material and entities that are at least composed primarily of some rock.

A particle of sand is a type of particle that is a union of something that is at least part of some sand and something that at least derives from part of some sand. It is disjoint with sand itself. The particle of sand is defined as a particle which 1) is composed primarily of and derived from rock or mineral sources and 2) is or was part of a portion of sand. Additionally, a particle of sand has exact synonyms including grain of sand, granule of sand, and sand granule.

A piece of gravel is a type of piece of rock and also falls under the category of items that are either at least part of some gravel or derive from part of some gravel. Additionally, a piece of gravel is defined as a piece of rock which is between two and 64 millimetres in length along its largest dimension.

Ice cap dome is a type of elevated and surface landform, which is at least part of some ice caps and has the quality of being domed. It is defined as a comparatively elevated area on an ice cap. Additionally, "ice mass" is considered a broad synonym for ice cap dome, while "icecap dome" is both an exact and a narrow synonym for it.

A particle of silt is a type of particle that is part of or derived from at least some part of silt. It is defined as a particle which is primarily composed of quartz or feldspar and is or was part of a portion of silt. Furthermore, a particle of silt is exactly synonymous with both a grain of silt and a granule of silt.

A grain of desert sand is identical to something that intersects with both a particle of sand and something that constitutes at least part of some desert sand. Furthermore, a grain of desert sand is classified as a type of particle of sand. Additionally, it is also considered a type of entity that forms at least part of some desert sand.

A grain of beach sand is the same as something that intersects with both a particle of sand and something that is at least part of some beach sand. Additionally, a grain of beach sand is a type of particle of sand and is also a type of something that is at least part of some beach sand.

A grain of acid dune sand is the same as something that intersects with a particle of sand and something that is at least part of some acid dune sand. Additionally, a grain of acid dune sand is a type of particle of sand and also a type of something that is at least part of some acid dune sand.

A grain of sea sand is the same as something that intersects between a particle of sand and something that is at least part of some sea sand. Additionally, a grain of sea sand is a type of particle of sand and is also a type of something that is at least part of some sea sand.

A grain of rocky sand is equivalent to the intersection of a particle of sand and something that is at least part of some rocky sand. Furthermore, a grain of rocky sand is classified as a type of particle of sand and also as a type of something that is at least part of some rocky sand.
A terrarium, which is a type of vivarium, is defined as a vivarium that simulates a terrestrial environment.
A Somma volcano is a type of volcano defined as a volcanic caldera that has been partially filled by a new central cone.

A volcanic arc is a type of archipelago and something that forms as a result of volcanic eruption. It is defined as a chain of volcanic islands or mountains formed by plate tectonics, specifically when an oceanic tectonic plate subducts under another tectonic plate, producing magma.
A continental arc is a type of volcanic arc that is defined as a volcanic arc formed by the subduction of oceanic crust below continental crust.
An island arc is a type of volcanic arc that is defined as a volcanic arc formed by the subduction of oceanic crust beneath another oceanic crust on an adjacent tectonic plate.

A volcanic field is a type of geothermally active field and a type of area that includes parts capable of volcanic eruptions. It is defined as a geothermal field prone to localized volcanic activity. Furthermore, volcanic field is synonymously related to terms such as volcanic complex, volcanic group, and volcanic system.

A monogenetic volcanic field is a type of volcanic field characterized by its composition of small, scattered volcanic vents. These fields are distinguished by containing numerous monogenetic volcanoes, each known for experiencing only one short eruptive event. The occurrence of monogenetic fields is limited to areas where the magma supply to the volcano is insufficient or where the vents are neither sufficiently close nor large enough to develop plumbing systems that allow for the continuous feeding of magma.

A pyroclastic cone is a type of volcanic cone with a specific definition: it is a cone made of material ejected from a volcano, which can range from the finest particles. Unlike cinder cones, which are more uniform, pyroclastic cones can be found in or on larger features such as stratovolcanoes, shield volcanoes, and inside calderas, but they can also be an independent feature. They can range from a few meters in height and are usually formed by a single eruption. Furthermore, pyroclastic cone has an exact synonym: pyroclastic dome.

A lock is a type of transport feature characterized by its unique function as a device for raising and lowering boats between stretches of water of different levels on river and canal waterways. The distinguishing feature of a lock is its fixed chamber whose water level can be varied.

An area of protected biodiversity is a type of protected area and is defined as an area of land or of a body of water where, through legal or other effective means, management practices prioritize the protection and maintenance of biological diversity, and of natural and associated cultural resources. Furthermore, "protected area" is considered a broad synonym for an area of protected biodiversity.

A natural monument is a type of natural environment and also falls under the category of entities that include at least some part of a protected area. It is defined as a natural environment which has been designated by a competent authority as having outstanding or unique value because of its rarity, aesthetic qualities, or cultural significance. Additionally, the term "natural monument" is broadly synonymous with the term "monument."

The area of national forest is a type of area of protected biodiversity and is defined as a protected forest or woodland area in the United States. National forests, which are controlled by the federal government and managed by the United States Forest Service under the direction of the United States Department of Agriculture, have the broad synonym "national forest."

A Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) is a type of area designated for the protection of biodiversity, characterized by its conservation designation that denotes a protected area in the United Kingdom. SSSIs serve as the fundamental 'building block' of nature conservation legislation, with most other legal nature/geological conservation designations, including National Nature Reserves, Ramsar Sites, Special Protection Areas, and Special Areas of Conservation, being based upon them. Additionally, a Site of Special Scientific Interest is also known by its synonyms, Area of Special Scientific Interest and SSSI.

Marine park area is a type of area of protected biodiversity, defined as a protected area of the sea usually established to preserve a specific habitat and ensure the ecosystem is sustained for the organisms that exist there. Most marine parks are designated by governments and are organized like watery national parks. Furthermore, marine park area has a broad synonym: marine park.

An area designated as a nature reserve is a type of area of protected biodiversity. It is defined as a protected area of importance for wildlife, flora, fauna, or features of geological or other special interest, which is reserved and managed for conservation and to provide special opportunities for study or research. Nature reserves may be designated by government institutions in some countries, such as the United Kingdom, or by private landowners, such as charities and research institutions, regardless of nationality. Additionally, an area designated as a nature reserve is also known by related synonyms such as natural preserve, natural reserve, nature preserve, and nature reserve.

A National Wildlife Refuge is a type of wildlife management area and is defined as a designation for certain protected areas of the United States managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service. The National Wildlife Refuge system represents a network of lands and waters managed with the aim of protecting wildlife and wildlife habitat.

A Ramsar site is a type of area designated as a nature reserve, defined as a wetland protected by the terms of the Ramsar Convention (The Convention on Wetlands of International Importance, especially as Waterfowl Habitat).

An area designated as a national nature reserve is a type of area of protected biodiversity, which is defined as an area of protected biodiversity that is of national significance for biological or Earth science interest. Moreover, it is broadly synonymous with the term national nature reserve.

An IUCN National Park is a type of area that is protected according to IUCN guidelines. It is defined as an IUCN protected area which primarily consists of ecosystems that are able to maintain their natural composition, structure, and function at a regional scale and are deemed to be representative of a region's natural bio- and geodiversity. Additionally, it is sufficiently large to allow its constituent ecosystems to function, develop, and recover from natural perturbations without human intervention. It is managed to preserve natural ecosystem integrity and functioning at a regional scale, while allowing human access for the purposes of conservation, cultural and spiritual activities, research, education, tourism, subsistence use by indigenous communities, and recreation. An IUCN National Park is broadly synonymous with a national park.

An ephemeral island is a type of island characterized by its temporary existence. It is usually formed as a result of the activity of a submarine volcano and only exists for a short period or short periods of time after its formation. Eventually, it is either eroded away or disappears beneath the surface of a body of water.

A brine pool is a type of lentic water body, hydroform, and is part of some ocean to a certain extent. It is defined as a large area of brine on the ocean basin near cold seep vents, which release methane into the water. These pools are concentrations of water with an extremely high salinity compared to the surrounding ocean. This high salinity is caused by the motion of large salt deposits through salt tectonics. Marine brine pools, which are the same as brine pools, are bodies of water with a salinity three to five times greater than that of the surrounding ocean. The source of the salt in deep-sea brine pools is the dissolution of large salt deposits through salt tectonics. The brine often contains high concentrations of methane, which provides energy to chemosynthetic animals living near the pool. Additionally, brine pool is exactly synonymous with marine brine pool.
Tuya is a type of volcano that is defined as a distinctive, flat-topped, steep-sided volcano formed when lava erupts through a thick glacier or ice sheet.

A complex volcano, also exactly known as a compound volcano, is a type of volcano characterized by having more than one feature. This formation occurs due to changes in their eruptive characteristics or the presence of multiple vents within an area. Specifically, stratovolcanoes can evolve into complex volcanoes as they may overlap another due to explosive eruptions, lava flows, pyroclastic flows, and through repeated eruptions, leading to the creation of multiple summits and vents. Additionally, stratovolcanoes might form a large caldera that becomes filled with multiple small cinder cones, lava domes, and craters, which can also develop on the caldera's rim.

A pyroclastic shield volcano is a type of shield volcano, which is defined as a shield volcano that is formed mostly of pyroclastic and highly explosive eruptions rather than relatively fluid basaltic lava issuing from vents or fissures on the surface of the volcano. These volcanoes typically display low-angle flank slopes and have little or no central collapse, although a shallow sag in the shield is commonly observed. Lava is commonly extruded after the cessation of explosive activity, commonly superposing the vent region. Pyroclastic shield volcano has exact synonyms: ignimbrite shield volcano and terrestrial ignimbrite shield.
A wildlife management area is a type of area of protected biodiversity, defined as a protected area with the purpose of protecting and managing wildlife.

A World Heritage Site is a type of protected area defined as a specific site, such as a forest, mountain, lake, desert, monument, building, complex, or city, that has been nominated and confirmed for inclusion on the list maintained by the International World Heritage Programme, which is administered by the UNESCO World Heritage Committee.

A biosphere reserve is a type of area dedicated to the protection of biodiversity and has been granted an international conservation designation by UNESCO under its Programme on Man and the Biosphere (MAB).

An artificial lake is a type of lake and human construction, specifically something that is formed as a result of some human-directed construction process. It is defined as a lake that is purposefully constructed.
A canal head reservoir is a type of reservoir constructed for the purpose of maintaining water levels in a canal or canals.

Inundation disposition, which is a type of environmental disposition, is defined as the disposition of an environmental system to be covered by liquid water. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym: flooding disposition.

An ice shelf is a type of caro 0000003 and a type of land ice mass. It is characterized by being at least partially surrounded by some atmosphere and possesses some buoyancy. Additionally, an ice shelf is adjacent to some marine water body and forms as a result of snowfall and mass ice flow. It is also attached to an intersection of a planetary landmass and something that is at least contained in some sea coast. The definition of an ice shelf includes an ice mass which is attached to the coast, has a minimum thickness of 2 meters, forms where a glacier or ice mass flows down to a coastline and onto the ocean surface, and grows by annual snow accumulation or by the seaward extension of land glaciers.

A massif is a type of elevated landform and is defined as a section of the Earth's crust that is demarcated by faults or flexures. In the movement of the crust, a massif tends to retain its internal structure while being displaced as a whole.

Lake shore is equivalent to the intersection of a shore and an entity that at least partially overlaps the coast of a lake. It is categorized under shores and is defined as the part of the land that is in immediate contact with a lake. Furthermore, lake shore is considered a part of, or at least overlaps, the coast of a lake. Additionally, lakeshore is a related synonym to lake shore.

A stream bed is a type of submerged bed and is something that is at least adjacent to some stream. It is defined as the channel bottom of a stream; the physical confine of the normal water flow. Additionally, "stream bottom" is an exact synonym for stream bed, while "dry stream bed" is considered a narrow synonym. Moreover, "stream channel" is a related synonym to stream bed.

A river bed is a type of stream bed and is also a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some river. It is defined as the channel bottom of a river; the physical confine of the normal water flow. Furthermore, river bed has a broad synonym, which is watercourse, and an exact synonym, which is river bottom.

A stream mouth is the place where a stream discharges into a lagoon, lake, or the sea, which is the same as the intersection of something that is a mouth and something that is at least part of some stream. It is a type of mouth, a type of hydroform, and a type of something that is at least part of some stream. Additionally, stream mouth has a broad synonym: stream.

A river mouth is defined as the end of a stream where it enters a standing water body, such as a lake, sea, or ocean. It is characterized by being the same as an intersection of a mouth and at least part of a river. Additionally, a river mouth is considered a type of stream mouth and is also categorized as a type of entity that is at least part of some river.

A container of an intermittent lake is a type of container of an intermittent water body and is defined as a depression which intermittently contains a lake. It has a broad synonym "lake," and its exact synonyms are "intermittent lake" and "intermittent lakes."

An intermittent wetland is a type of wetland ecosystem defined as a wetland ecosystem which is sometimes inundated or saturated by surface or ground water sufficient to support, and that under normal circumstances does support, a prevalence of vegetation typically adapted for life in saturated soil conditions.
A mountain spur is a type of spur and is part of a mountain, or at least a portion of it. It is defined as a spur that is a component of a mountain.

A land bridge is a type of isthmus with a definition that encompasses an isthmus or other land connection between what at other times are separate land masses, enabling animals and plants to cross and colonize new lands. These land bridges are typically formed due to regression, where sea levels fall, revealing previously submerged sections of continental shelf. Furthermore, land bridges can also be formed by upthrust at the edge of continental plates and by the retreat of glaciers, which alleviates pressure on shallow marine formations.

An ice tongue is a type of floating ice mass and a type of land ice mass, which forms at least part of some valley glacier. It is defined as a long and narrow sheet of ice projecting out from the coastline, forming when a valley glacier moves very rapidly out into the ocean or a lake. Additionally, "glacier tongue" is an exact synonym for ice tongue, and it is also relatedly referred to as a "glacial tongue."

A sound is a type of coastal inlet that is defined as a large sea or ocean inlet, which is larger than a bay, deeper than a bight, wider than a fjord, or it may identify a narrow sea or ocean channel between two bodies of land.

A strait is a type of channel and watercourse that connects at least some water bodies. It is defined as a narrow channel of water that connects two larger bodies of water, thus lying between two land masses. Furthermore, "strait" has broad synonyms such as "channel" and "watercourse."

A channel of a watercourse is a type of depressed landform, and it is also a type that encompasses entities that have at least some part of a bank and a submerged bed. Furthermore, a channel of a watercourse is defined as a depressed landform that physically confines a river, slough, or ocean strait, consisting of a bed and banks.
A marine channel is a type of channel of a watercourse, defined as a channel of a watercourse that contains marine water.

A lake channel is the same as something that intersects with something that is a channel of a watercourse and something that is at least a location of some lake. It is a type of channel of a watercourse and also a type of something that is at least located in some lake. Moreover, a lake channel is defined as a channel of a watercourse which contains lake water.

A volcanic cone is a type of volcanic feature, elevated landform, and something that has at least some conical quality. It is defined as being built by fragments, known as ejecta, that are thrown up from a volcanic vent, accumulating around the vent in the shape of a cone with a central crater. Furthermore, "cone" is considered a broad synonym for a volcanic cone, while "lava cone" is an exact synonym. Additionally, "cone (geological)" is a related synonym.

An ash cone is a type of volcanic cone, specifically one that is composed primarily of volcanic ash. It is defined as a cone consisting of particles ranging from silt to sand size, produced by explosive eruptions from a vent where magma interacts with groundwater or the sea, such as in an offshore eruption. These eruptions, termed phreatic, involve the expansion of steam and volcanic gases, leading to the ejection of small particles known as ash. This ash, having the consistency of flour when it falls, forms an unconsolidated ash cone. Once the ash consolidates, the structure becomes known as a tuff cone or tuff ring.

A cinder cone is a type of volcanic cone, primarily composed of tephra, scoria, and pumice. It can be defined as a cone built almost entirely of loose volcanic fragments called cinders, which include pumice, pyroclastics, or tephra. These particles and blobs of congealed lava are ejected from a single vent, and as the gas-charged lava is blown violently into the air, it breaks into small fragments that solidify and fall as cinders around the vent, forming a circular or oval cone. Most cinder cones feature a bowl-shaped crater at the summit. Additionally, cinder cone is synonymously related to the term mount.

A spatter cone is a type of volcanic cone defined as a volcanic cone formed of molten lava ejected from a vent somewhat like taffy. Expanding gases in the lava fountains tear the liquid rock into irregular gobs that fall back to earth, forming a heap around the vent. The still partly liquid rock splashed down and over the sides of the developing mound, called spatter, is not fully solid when it lands. The individual deposits are very irregular in shape and weld together as they cool, which particularly differentiates them from cinder and ash.

A mud volcano is a type of volcano characterized by the creation through geologically excreted liquids and gases, with several different processes potentially causing such activity. Notably, the temperatures involved are much cooler than those associated with igneous processes.
A shield volcano is a type of volcano characterized by its large size and shallowly-sloping sides. It is also related to the term "mount" as a synonym.

A stratovolcano is a type of volcano that is tall and conical, composed of many layers of hardened lava, tephra, and volcanic ash. These volcanoes are characterized by a steep profile and periodic, explosive eruptions. The lava that flows from stratovolcanoes is viscous and cools and hardens before spreading far. The source magma of stratovolcanoes is classified as acidic, or high in silica to intermediate, including rhyolite, dacite, or andesite. Additionally, stratovolcano is also known as a composite volcano, which is a related synonym.

A mid-ocean ridge is a type of range of seamounts, and it is a feature found in at least part of some oceans. Additionally, it is formed as a result of divergent tectonic movements. The definition of a mid-ocean ridge is an underwater mountain range formed by plate tectonics. This process involves the uplifting of the ocean floor, which occurs when convection currents rise in the mantle beneath the oceanic crust, creating magma where two tectonic plates meet at a divergent boundary. The mid-ocean ridges of the world are interconnected, forming a single global mid-oceanic ridge system that is a component of every ocean. Furthermore, "OceanRidge" is a related synonym for mid-ocean ridge.

A subglacial volcano is a type of volcano that is at least adjacent to something which is a union of a glacier and a glacial lake. It is defined as a volcano produced by subglacial eruptions or eruptions beneath the surface of a lake melted into a glacier or ice mass by the rising lava. Additionally, a subglacial volcano is also related to and synonymously known as a tuya.

A volcanic fissure is a type of volcano characterized by a linear volcanic vent through which lava erupts, typically without any explosive activity. The vent, often only a few meters wide, can extend for many kilometers. Fissure vents are known to cause large flood basalts and channels, and the volcano itself usually appears as a crack either on the ground or on the ocean floor. Narrow fissures may become filled with hardening lava. Additionally, "fissure" and "fissure vent" are related synonyms for a volcanic fissure.

A whirlpool is a type of marine current and is defined as a large, swirling body of water produced by ocean tides. It is broadly synonymous with the term hydrographic feature and has an exact synonym, WHRL.

Kipuka is a type of elevated and surface landform, defined as an elevated area such as a hill, ridge, or old lava dome located inside or downslope from an area of active volcanism. When new lava flows cover the surrounding land, the kipuka becomes isolated, making it appear as a (usually) forested island in a barren lava flow.
Ford is a type of transport feature and is defined as the shallow part of a stream which can be easily crossed. It has a broad synonym, transportation feature, and an exact synonym, ford (crossing).

A tidal watercourse is a type of watercourse and also falls under the category of entities that at least contain some tidal flow process. It is defined as a watercourse which has the intensity and direction of its flow primarily determined by the tides.

Pingo is a type of elevated and surface landform, characterized by being at least partially composed of ice mass and surrounded by soil. It is defined as a mound of earth-covered ice found in the Arctic, subarctic, and Antarctica, which can reach up to 70 metres in height and up to 2 kilometres in diameter. Pingo has a broad synonym, mount, and exact synonyms including hydrolaccolith and pingos. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as bugor and bulginniakh.

A natural arch is a type of surface landform defined as a natural formation where a rock arch forms, with a natural passageway through underneath. It is exactly synonymous with both arches (natural formation) and natural bridge, and is also relatedly synonymous with sea arch.

A raised beach is a type of beach characterized by a beach or wave cut platform that is raised above the shoreline due to a relative fall in the sea level. Additionally, it is synonymous with the term "terrace."

A coastal dune is defined as a dune that is part of a coast. It represents the intersection of a dune and an entity that is at least in part part of some sea coast. Moreover, a coastal dune is characterized as a type of dune as well as a type of entity that is, to some extent, part of a sea coast.
Machair is a type of raised beach and is defined as a fertile low-lying raised beach found on some of the coastlines of Ireland and Scotland, particularly in the Outer Hebrides.

Ria is a type of valley with a specific definition as a submergent coastal landform. It forms where sea levels rise relative to the land, either due to eustatic sea level change, where the global sea levels rise, or isostatic sea level change, where the land sinks. This process results in valleys, which were previously at sea level, becoming submerged. Ria is also related to several synonyms, including drowned river valley, drowned valley, and valley.

Stack is a type of elevated and surface landform. It is a type of entity that at least has a part that is an intersection of rock and an entity that at least has a quality of being columnar. Moreover, a stack is a type of entity that is at least partially surrounded by an entity that is a union of the ocean and the sea, and it is a type of entity that at least overlaps some sea coast. Stack has the definition of being a geological landform consisting of a steep and often vertical column or columns of rock in the sea near a coast.

A tombolo is a type of bar and is also considered a depositional landform such as a spit or bar. It forms a narrow piece of land between an island or offshore rock and a mainland shore, or between two islands or offshore rocks. This usually occurs because the island causes wave refraction, depositing sand and shingle moved by longshore drift in each direction around the island where the waves meet. Eustatic sea level rise may also contribute to its formation as material is pushed up with rising sea levels. Furthermore, a tombolo is characterized by being at least partially surrounded by an intersection of the ocean and the sea, and at least adjacent to a union of an island, a rocky reef, and a shore. It is formed as a result of some depositional process. Additionally, "bar" and "island" are related synonyms to tombolo.

A wave cut platform is a type of surface landform, which is also known as a marine terrace. It is a part of some sea cliffs, characterized as the narrow flat area often seen at the base of a sea cliff. This is caused by the action of the waves, defining its unique nature and formation.
Limestone pavement is a type of karst and is defined as a natural karst landform consisting of a flat, incised surface of exposed limestone that resembles artificial pavement.

A river island is equivalent to an entity that is both an island and is located in a river. It is a specific type of island as well as a type of geographical feature that is situated in a river. River island is defined as an island that lies in a river. Additionally, river island is associated with synonyms such as ait, eyot, and fluvial island.

A lake island is defined as an island that lies in a lake, which represents the intersection of something that is an island and something that is at least located in some lake. Furthermore, a lake island is categorized as a type of island and also as a type of entity that is at least located in some lake.

The ocean floor is a type of marine bed and is considered a part of at least some ocean basin as well as being adjacent to some oceans. It is defined as a marine bed that lies below an ocean. Additionally, the ocean floor is exactly synonymous with the ocean bed and has related synonyms such as ocean floor feature and seafloor.

Meander is a type of liquid astronomical body part and is also a type of something that forms at least part of some stream. It is defined as a bend in a stream, specifically when a stream flowing through a wide valley or flat plain tends to form meanders as it alternatively erodes and deposits sediments along its course. In terms of synonyms, meander has a broad synonym of watercourse and a narrow synonym of stream. Additionally, it has a related synonym, oxbow loop.

A biome is a type of ecosystem that constitutes at least a part of the biosphere, and it is determined by an ecological community. It is characterized by having at least two habitat components. Biomes are distinct from ecoregions and ecozones, indicating no overlap between them. The definition of a biome highlights that it is an ecosystem to which resident ecological communities have evolved adaptations. Furthermore, "major habitat type" is an exact synonym for biome, and it is also relatedly synonymous with "EcosystemType."

An arete is a type of ridge that possesses certain qualities; it is angular and slender. Moreover, it is adjacent to features that are either a cirque or a glacial valley. An arete is also formed as a result of a glacial erosion process. It is defined as a jagged, narrow ridge that separates glacier valleys or cirques, and it is related to the synonym "ridge."

A dirt cone is a type of surface landform that is closely associated with ice masses, indicating that it is adjacent to or interacts with them. It is the result of a depositional process, specifically emerging from an intersection of melting activities and the involvement of water ice that is part of a glacier. Essentially, a dirt cone is defined as a feature of a glacier where dirt, having fallen into a hollow in the ice, forms a coating that insulates the ice below. This results in the surrounding ice melting away, leaving the dirt cone behind.

A drumlin field is a type of hill range and is characterized as something that includes, at the very least, a portion of a drumlin. It is defined as a cluster of dozens to hundreds of similarly shaped, sized, and oriented drumlins. Additionally, a drumlin field is synonymously related to a drumlin swarm.

A monadnock is a type of mount characterized as an isolated hill, knob, ridge, or small mountain that rises abruptly from a gently sloping or virtually level surrounding plain. It is related to several synonyms including inselberg, kopje, and mount.

Kame terrace is the same as something that is both a terrace and at least located in some kame. It is a type of terrace and also a type of something that is at least located in some kame. Additionally, kame terrace is defined as a terrace associated with a kame.
An outwash fan is a type of plain characterized by a fan-shaped body of sediments deposited by braided streams from a melting glacier.

A proglacial lake is a type of glacial lake, defined as a lake formed either by the damming action of a moraine or an ice dam during the retreat of a melting glacier, or one formed by meltwater trapped against an ice mass due to isostatic depression of the crust around the ice. Additionally, proglacial lake is broadly synonymous with the term "lake."

A tunnel valley is a type of glacial valley characterized by its deep but narrow nature with a 'U' shaped cross-section and frequently a 'U' shaped plan, often found filled with glacial till. It is typically formed when the edge of an ice mass advances up a slope, and its length can range from centimeters to kilometers, depending on the circumstances of formation. Additionally, tunnel valley is synonymously related to "rinnental" and "tunnel-vale."
Nye Channel is a type of tunnel valley, which is defined as a small tunnel valley.
Alas is a type of landform characterized by being both depressed and a surface feature. It is defined as a steep-sided depression formed by the melting of permafrost, which may contain a lake.

Dell is a type of valley that encompasses entities possessing at least some quality that aligns with being either U-shaped or V-shaped. Furthermore, Dell is defined as a small wooded valley, which can be either U- or V-shaped, and it broadly synonymous with valley.
A rock shelter, which is a type of cave, is defined as a shallow cave-like opening at the base of a bluff or cliff. It also has a related synonym, rockhouse.
Terracette is a type of ridge that is defined as a ridge on a hillside formed when saturated soil particles expand, then contract as they dry, causing them to move slowly downhill.
Maelstrom is a type of whirlpool, specifically defined as a very powerful whirlpool.

A flood control reservoir is a type of reservoir defined as a structure constructed for the purpose of containing a flood, which is an overflow of water from a body of water that submerges land. It is exactly synonymous with a flood control basin and is relatedly referred to as both a retention basin and a storage basin.

A woodland clearing is a type of field that is characterized by having some exposed quality. It is also defined as a tract of land with few or no trees and is surrounded by areas that are either woodland areas or forested areas, indicating it is at least surrounded by a combination of these two. The exact synonyms for a woodland clearing include "CLEARING" and "clearing," while it has a narrow synonym, "forest clearing." Related synonyms for a woodland clearing encompass "burn," "burnt over area," "clearing," "cut line," "fire break," "glade," "grassland," "logged area," and "opening."

Transvasement, a type of aqueduct, is defined as an aqueduct designed to transport water from one river basin to another in order to address issues of hydrographic imbalance. It has the capability to mitigate floods by relocating water to drought-affected areas.

A terrestrial biome is equivalent to an intersection of a biome and an entity at least determined by a union of a planetary landmass and an entity that is at least part of a planetary landmass. It is a type of biome and specifically, it is a type determined by an entity that is at least determined by a union of a planetary landmass and an entity that is at least part of a planetary landmass. The terrestrial biome is defined as a biome that is primarily or completely situated on a landmass. Additionally, it has a related synonym, which is the terrestrial realm.

The marine biome is the same as the intersection of an aquatic biome and something that is at least determined by some marine water body. It is a type of aquatic biome as well as a type of marine ecosystem. The marine biome is defined as an aquatic biome which is determined by a marine water body. Furthermore, it has a related synonym, marine realm.
A hydroelectric reservoir is a type of reservoir that is constructed for the purpose of generating electricity.
A drinking water reservoir is a type of reservoir that is constructed for the purpose of providing drinking water.
An irrigation reservoir is a type of reservoir that is constructed for the purpose of providing water for irrigation.
An amenity lake is a type of artificial lake that is constructed, or modified, for the chief purpose of providing an amenity.

A ribbon lake is a specific type of lake characterized by its long, narrow, and finger-shaped appearance, commonly located in a glacial trough. The process of its formation starts when a glacier traverses over an area composed of alternating bands of hard and soft bedrock. The glacier carries sharp-edged boulders at its base, which preferentially erode the softer rock through a process called abrasion, leading to the creation of a depression known as a rock basin. Adjacent to the rock basin, the less eroded, more resistant rock forms outcrops called rock bars, serving as natural barriers. These rock bars function as dams, allowing rainwater to collect between them after the glacier recedes, subsequently filling the rock basin and resulting in the formation of a ribbon lake. Additionally, ribbon lakes can form behind natural barriers such as terminal or recessional moraines, which similarly act as dams that facilitate the accumulation of water. Another scenario for the formation of a ribbon lake occurs when a tributary glacier merges with a main glacier, increasing the erosional power and creating a trough. This trough can then be filled with river water or meltwater, further contributing to the creation of a ribbon lake.

Liman is a type of lentic water body, defined as a lake or estuary that is formed at the mouth of a river where flow is blocked by a bar of sediments. This bar can be created either by the current of a sea, making it maritime, or by the flow of a bigger river at the confluence, making it fluvial.

A turlough is a type of container of an intermittent lake, defined as a container of an intermittent lake unique to the limestone areas of Ireland, mostly west of the River Shannon. Most turloughs flood in the autumn, usually sometime in October, and then dry up sometime between April and July.
Tarn is a type of lake and has an exact synonym, corrie loch. It is defined as a mountain lake that is formed in a cirque excavated by a glacier, and a moraine may form a natural dam below a tarn.
A tidewater glacier is a type of glacier that is at least adjacent to an ocean. It is defined as a glacier which terminates in a lake or the sea, with the terminus either floating or grounded.

A plateau glacier is a type of glacier and also falls under the category of things that are at least adjacent to some plateau. It is defined as a glacier on a plateau or high area, which is smaller than an ice sheet.

A valley glacier is a type of glacier that is characterized by flowing for all or most of its length within the walls of a valley. As a result, it has a distinct tongue and a well-defined outline and descends from either high mountains, from an ice cap on a plateau, or from an ice sheet. This type of glacier is not only partially or entirely surrounded by a valley but also situated adjacent to some valley.
An outlet glacier is a type of glacier that is fed by an ice sheet.
Penplain is a type of plain, defined as a region of low topographic relief resulting from erosion by streams.

A pseudocrater, which is a type of crater, is defined as a volcanic landform that resembles a true volcanic crater but differs in that it does not serve as an actual vent from which lava has erupted. Unlike genuine craters, pseudocraters lack any magma conduit connecting below the Earth's surface. They are formed by steam explosions when flowing hot lava comes into contact with a wet surface, such as a swamp, lake, or pond. The explosive gases breach the lava surface in a manner akin to a phreatic eruption, leading to the accumulation of tephra that builds up into forms resembling true volcanic craters. Additionally, a pseudocrater is precisely known as a rootless vent.

A polygenetic volcanic field is a type of volcanic field characterized by scattered volcanic vents. It is defined as a volcanic field containing numerous polygenetic volcanoes, which are distinguished by having more than one eruptive event from the same vent(s), in contrast to the more common monogenetic volcanic field. Polygenetic volcanic fields typically occur where there is a high-level magma chamber. These fields may exhibit lithological discontinuities, which can be attributed to major changes in magma chemistry, volcanotectonic events, or long erosional intervals, and their formation may span a period of more than 10 million years.
A harbour, which is an exact synonym for harbor, is a type of surface landform defined as a landform that provides shelter from atmospheric weather and marine currents, waves, and other dynamics.
An artificial harbor is a type of human construction and a type of harbor, defined as a harbor constructed by human agency. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "artificial harbour."

A natural harbor is a type of harbor that is formed by a natural landform where a part of a body of water is protected and deep enough to furnish anchorage. Furthermore, the term "natural harbor" has the exact synonym "natural harbour."

A university campus is a type of educational facility that is characterized by being an area of land on which a college or university and related institutional buildings are situated. It is also described as a type of entity that must include at least some parts that are buildings, and it specifically requires at least 2 building components to qualify under this classification. Furthermore, the term "university campus" is broadly synonymous with "campus."
A hydroelectric dam is a type of dam that is constructed for the purpose of generating electricity from the water stored behind it.
A research facility is a type of human construction defined as a facility, permanent or temporary, on land, in air, space, or water, where scientific research or measurements can be undertaken.
An irrigation dam is a type of dam that is constructed for the purpose of holding water in a reservoir for irrigation.
A flood control dam is a type of dam constructed for the purpose of controlling flooding.
Backwater is a type of watercourse and is defined as an area of calm water unaffected by the current of a stream. Moreover, it is broadly synonymous with wetland and has an exact synonym, BACKWATER.

A gravel pit is essentially a quarry from which gravel is extracted, sharing similarities with any entity that intersects with both a quarry and an entity capable of a material extraction process that outputs gravel. This makes a gravel pit not only a type of quarry but also categorizes it as an entity with gravel as a part and is capable of a material extraction process that results in gravel. Furthermore, a gravel pit is defined as a quarry for gravel extraction and is synonymously related to a mine site.

Cut is a type of anthropogenic geographic feature, defined as an excavation of the Earth's surface to provide passage for a road, railway, canal, etc. It has exact synonyms including "CUT" and "cutting."

An inlet is a type of hydrographic feature, which is part of a water body and is at least partially surrounded by a planetary landmass. It is defined as an opening of the sea into the land, or of a lake into its shore. Related synonyms for inlet include anse, arm, firth, and ria.

A lake inlet is defined as an opening of a lake into its shore. It is identified as being the same as an intersection of an inlet and at least part of a lake. Furthermore, a lake inlet is categorized as a type of inlet and also as a type of entity that is at least partially part of a lake.
Mount is a type of elevated landform, defined as a mountain or a hill. It has several related synonyms, including cerrito, cerro, dome, koppje, and monadnock.

The range of mounts is categorized as a type of field, which is also considered a type of entity that overlaps some mount and is characterized by having at least 2 mount components. It is defined as a field that encompasses at least two mounts connected by high ground and arranged in an approximately linear fashion. Additionally, the range of mounts is synonymously related to the term "range (physiographic)."

A mouth is a type of watercourse and also a type of entity that at least overlaps some water body. Additionally, it is defined as something that has at least 2 water body components. The term "mouth" is specifically defined as the exit or point of discharge of a stream into another stream, lake, or sea. It has an exact synonym, "MOUTH," and a related synonym, "outlet."

Peak is a type of landform and is part of some elevated landform. It is defined as the summit of a mountain. The term "peak" has an exact synonym, which is "peaks." Additionally, it has several related synonyms including "ahu," "ice peak," "mountain crest," "mountain summit," "nunatak," and "summit."

Pinnacle refers to a type of elevated landform that is characterized by its quality of protruding out. It is defined as a tall, slender, spire-shaped rock projecting from a level or more gently sloping surface. Pinnacle is broadly synonymous with the term natural rock formation and has exact synonyms including "PINNACLE" and "pinnacle (natural formation)." Additionally, related synonyms for pinnacle encompass terms such as chapeirao, coral head, crag, pillar, and scar.

The sea floor is a type of marine bed and is something that is at least adjacent to some sea. It is defined as a marine bed which lies below a sea. The sea floor has exact synonyms including Meeresboden, SeaFloor, fondale marino, fondo marino, ocean floor, seabed, and seafloor. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as ocean floor, sea bed, 海床, and 海底.

Plunge pools are a type of water body and a specific form of hydroform, characterized by being part of, or at least formed as a result of, some stream and planetary erosion. They are defined as a hollow eroded by the force of the falling water at the base of a waterfall, particularly by the eddying effect. Additionally, plunge pools are exactly synonymous with PLUNGE POOL.

A polynya is a type of sea surface layer and is defined as a sea surface layer that is not covered by ice and is laterally surrounded by either pack ice or a combination of land and pack ice. It is also known by several exact synonyms: POLYNA, Polyn'ya, Polynya, and polynia. Additionally, polynya has related synonyms that include big clearing, clearing, glade, ice clearing, and regional clearing.

Sea shore is the same as something that intersects with something that is a shore and something that at least overlaps some sea coast. It is a type of shore and also a type of something that at least overlaps some sea coast. Moreover, sea shore is defined as that part of the land in immediate contact with a sea, including the intertidal zone. Additionally, sea shore has a related synonym, which is shore.

A shoreline is a type of two-dimensional continuant fiat boundary that is at least part of some shore. It is defined as a boundary located between a landmass and a water body. The term "shoreline" has exact synonyms, including "Küstenlinie," "Shoreline," "linea costiera," and "línea costera." Additionally, it has a narrow synonym, "海岸線," and related synonyms such as "SHOR" and "coastline."

Paternoster Lake is a type of glacial lake and is defined as one of a series of glacial lakes connected by a single stream or a braided stream system. Additionally, Paternoster Lake has a broad synonym: lake.

A glacial lake is a type of lake that is primarily composed of meltwater. It forms as a result of a glacial erosion process, filling a depression created by this process. Essentially, a glacial lake is defined as a lake which owes its presence to the erosion and meltwater from glaciers.

Palsa is a type of frost heave defined as a frost heave that forms due to a perennial ice lens forming under the soil, which pushes a roughly oval portion of the land surface upwards. It falls within a category that intersects with wetland ecosystems and permafrost, indicating it is part of both these environmental features. Additionally, a palsa is characterized by being part of an entity that intersects with ice lenses and is surrounded by a combination of permafrost and soil, suggesting it incorporates elements of both in its formation. Palsa is also exactly synonymous with both palsa bog and palsamoor, indicating these terms can be used interchangeably to describe this natural phenomenon.

A consequent stream is a type of stream defined as one whose course is a direct consequence of the original slope of the surface upon which it developed, meaning it follows the slope of the original land.

A subsequent stream is a type of stream defined as one whose course has been determined by selective headward erosion along weak strata. These streams have generally developed after the original stream, indicating that subsequent streams developed independently of the original relief of the land. Typically, they follow paths determined by the weak rock belts.

A resequent stream is a type of stream defined as one whose course adheres to the original relief, albeit at a lower level than the original slope, flowing down a course determined by the underlying strata in the same direction. These streams, which develop later, are generally tributaries to a subsequent stream.
An obsequent stream is a type of stream that is defined as flowing in the opposite direction of the consequent drainage. It is broadly synonymous with the term watercourse.

An insequent stream is a type of stream characterized by an almost random drainage that often forms dendritic patterns. These streams, which are typically tributaries, have developed through headward erosion on a horizontally stratified belt or on homogeneous rocks. Importantly, the courses of these streams seem to be independent of the original slope of the surface, its structure, or the type of rock.

A tributary is defined as a stream or river which flows into another river (a parent river) or body of water but may not flow directly into the sea. It is identified as a type of stream and also as a type of entity that is at least a tributary of some hydrographic feature. Furthermore, a tributary is considered equivalent to the intersection of something that is a stream and something that is at least a tributary of a hydrographic feature. In terms of terminology, a tributary has the broad synonyms of 'stream' and 'watercourse', as well as the exact synonym 'affluent'. It is also relatedly referred to as an 'affluent stream', a 'confluent stream', and a 'river tributary'.

Rill is classified as both a type of depressed landform and a type of surface landform. It is defined as a narrow and shallow incision into soil resulting from erosion by overland flow that has been focused into a thin thread by soil surface roughness. The process of rill formation, known as rilling, is commonly observed on agricultural land and unvegetated ground.
Rincon is a type of meander and is defined as an incised meander on a river. Additionally, it is related to the synonym "inlet."

A volcanic dike is a type of igneous intrusion, dike, and something that at least formed as a result of some volcanic eruption. It is defined as an intrusive igneous body whose thickness is considerably smaller than its other two dimensions, varying from sub-centimeter scale to many meters in thickness, with lateral dimensions that can extend over many kilometers. Characterized by its intrusion into a cross-cutting fissure, a dike cuts across other pre-existing layers or bodies of rock, signifying that a dike is always younger than the rocks containing it. Typically, dikes are high angle to near vertical in orientation; however, subsequent tectonic deformation may rotate the sequence of strata through which the dike lies, making it horizontal. Additionally, a volcanic dike is broadly synonymous with a ridge and has exact synonyms including dyke (geologic), igneous dike, and volcanic dyke.

A trough is a type of depressed landform with a definition as a linear structural depression that extends laterally over a distance, being less steep than a trench. It can be a narrow basin or a geologic rift. Among various types, there are oceanic troughs found under oceans; examples include the rift along the mid-oceanic ridge and the Cayman Trough. Additionally, trough has a related synonym, swale.
A beaver dam is a type of animal habitation and it is defined as an obstruction in a stream constructed by a beaver. Additionally, it has a broad synonym, which is "dam."

A submerged bed is a type of solid surface layer and also serves as the surface of an astronomical body. It is characterized by being at least part of some depressed landform and adjacent to some water body. It is defined as the portion of the ground surface that lies below water. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with the term "BOTTOM."

A container of an intermittent saline lake is a type of container of an intermittent lake. It is defined as a depression that is periodically filled with saline water, forming a saline lake. Additionally, this container is broadly synonymous with a lake and has exact synonyms including intermittent saline lake, intermittent salt lake, and intermittent salt lakes.

A container of an intermittent oxbow lake is categorized as a type of oxbow lake and also as a type of container of an intermittent lake. It is defined as a depression that is continuous with one or more abandoned meander loops of a river channel. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with the term "intermittent oxbow lake."

A container of an intermittent pond is a type of container of an intermittent water body, defined as a container of an intermittent water body that, when filled with water, has a well-illuminated surface layer, is subject to complete mixing of the water it holds, and is smaller than the container of a lake. It has exact synonyms including intermittent pond, intermittent ponds, and intermittent pool. Moreover, it also has a narrow synonym and a related synonym, both referred to as intermittent pool.

An underground irrigation canal is both a type of irrigation canal and a type of underground water body, defined as a gently inclined underground tunnel that brings water for irrigation from an aquifer.

An intermittently filled reservoir, also known exactly as an intermittent reservoir, is defined as a type of container for an intermittent water body. Specifically, it is a reservoir that is not permanently filled with water and may be dry at times.

A Wadi mouth is defined as the lower terminus of a wadi where it widens into an adjoining floodplain, depression, or water body. It is a type of mouth and also a type of entity that is at least located in some wadi. Moreover, a Wadi mouth is the same as an intersection of a mouth and an entity that is at least located in some wadi.

A terrace is identified as a type of surface landform and falls under the category of entities that possess, at the very least, a portion characterized by a slope. It is defined as a step-like feature situated between areas of higher and lower ground, essentially a relatively flat or gently inclined shelf of earth, which is either backed and fronted by steep slopes or supported by manmade retaining walls. The term "TERRACE" serves as an exact synonym for terrace. Moreover, terrace is closely associated with a set of narrow synonyms including "bench," "ledge," "rock terrace," and another instance of "terrace" itself. Additionally, "bench" and "bench (natural)" are considered to be related synonyms to terrace.
